00:07:36.610 --> 00:07:38.990
Through these panels, we
will be exploring the concept

00:07:38.990 --> 00:07:42.220
of documenting the now,
with now oscillating

00:07:42.220 --> 00:07:45.930
between two poles,
1968 and 2018.

00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:48.990
Fifty years ago, Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. and a cohort

00:07:48.990 --> 00:07:51.230
of collaborators launched
an ambitious effort

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.660
to bring attention to the
plate of under-resourced

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:56.250
and underrepresented
communities across the country,

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:58.120
the Poor People's Campaign.

00:07:58.120 --> 00:08:00.380
Social justice and
advocacy intertwined

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:02.540
with cultural programming
and documentation during

00:08:02.540 --> 00:08:05.720
that campaign, especially
here on the mall in DC,

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:08.700
resulting in rich collections
held in the Library of Congress

00:08:08.700 --> 00:08:10.230
as well as its sister
institutions,

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:12.140
such as the Smithsonian
Center for Folklife

00:08:12.140 --> 00:08:14.420
and Cultural Heritage,
and the DC Public Library

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:16.270
Special Collections.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:19.220
What do these collections
let us understand?

00:08:19.220 --> 00:08:21.530
What can we do with these
materials and what does it mean

00:08:21.530 --> 00:08:24.790
to steward them at
public institutions?

00:08:24.790 --> 00:08:28.830
What do the materials tell us
about the then and the now?

00:08:28.830 --> 00:08:32.250
In 1968, the PPC was
part of a worldwide surge

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:34.980
in social justice movements
demanding human rights

00:08:34.980 --> 00:08:37.600
and focused on disrupting
the normalization of poverty,

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:40.270
racism or other systems
of exclusion

00:08:40.270 --> 00:08:43.680
that have shaped the middle
of the 20th century on.

00:08:43.680 --> 00:08:47.130
Roughly a generation-and-a-half
later, today, we find ourselves

00:08:47.130 --> 00:08:49.600
in parallel environment wherein
communities are coming together

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:53.620
to raise visibility, resist
exclusion, and demand change.

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:56.220
Again, we see the
intersection of social justice

00:08:56.220 --> 00:08:59.040
and cultural activity,
of art in action.

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:01.830
And the roles the cultural
documentation holds in an era

00:09:01.830 --> 00:09:04.550
of social media and what
scholar Richard Coyne refers

00:09:04.550 --> 00:09:07.390
to as the ubiquity
of digital devices.

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:08.990
As with the historical
collections,

00:09:08.990 --> 00:09:11.580
we might ponder what the
contemporaneous collections

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:14.240
of documentation
enable us to understand,

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:15.870
illustrate, and narrate.

00:09:15.870 --> 00:09:18.610
In other words, what
can we do as curators,

00:09:18.610 --> 00:09:20.870
reference specialists,
academics, activists

00:09:20.870 --> 00:09:24.250
or citizen scholars, with the
rich documentation being created

00:09:24.250 --> 00:09:25.760
in the moment?

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:28.490
We designed this symposium as an
opportunity for a cross-section

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:30.450
of those involved in
cultural movements

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:33.620
and the resultant collections,
to engage in conversations

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:35.690
