So I think that's
important to think about.

00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:11.910
All the activism
that has occurred

00:12:11.910 --> 00:12:15.300
over the last few years,
whether it's Black Lives Matter,

00:12:15.300 --> 00:12:18.640
Occupy or Standing Iraq
or other places like,

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:21.280
that the Women's March.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:24.900
So Guha asked me to do some
framing, I guess, initially,

00:12:24.900 --> 00:12:28.890
of just some larger
questions and I --

00:12:28.890 --> 00:12:32.330
some threads that both
my book addresses as well

00:12:32.330 --> 00:12:35.120
as just thinking about
social justice organizing

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:37.760
and coalition building
more generally.

00:12:37.760 --> 00:12:41.110
He also asked us
to think of what --

00:12:41.110 --> 00:12:44.840
to address why we care
about this, right?

00:12:44.840 --> 00:12:46.870
Why do we care about
this 50 years later,

00:12:46.870 --> 00:12:48.940
especially as a scholar
who wasn't born

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:52.890
when the Poor People's
Campaign was going on initially.

00:12:52.890 --> 00:12:54.700
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
Don't rub it in.

00:12:54.700 --> 00:12:56.000
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler: So sorry.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.670
Just -- I missed it by
a few years, all right?

00:12:58.670 --> 00:12:59.970
I was basically training

00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:02.540
as a traditional civil rights
historian at Duke University.

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:07.050
I wrote a master's thesis on
school desegregation in Florida,

00:13:07.050 --> 00:13:09.720
and I -- that's kind of
where I thought I would go.

00:13:09.720 --> 00:13:14.450
I would tell stories about
African American activism

00:13:14.450 --> 00:13:17.410
and the coalition with whites

00:13:17.410 --> 00:13:20.010
around making a more
just society.

00:13:20.010 --> 00:13:22.630
But what was interesting to
me and what intrigued me by --

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:27.920
soon after I moved to
Durham, North Carolina,

00:13:27.920 --> 00:13:33.820
was the great unease
that several generations

00:13:33.820 --> 00:13:35.970
of African American
activists in this --

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.870
in that city, which had a
rich tradition of activism,

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:42.510
both working-class through labor
organizing as well as a more

00:13:42.510 --> 00:13:48.740
of a late middle-class activism,
in Durham, that unease they had

00:13:48.740 --> 00:13:51.650
with the changing political
dynamics in this city

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:54.350
because of an influx of Latinos.

00:13:54.350 --> 00:13:55.650
And this is something that --

00:13:55.650 --> 00:13:58.920
of course, a phenomenon that
happened in the '80s and '90s

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:00.330
in the south in particular.

00:14:00.330 --> 00:14:04.710
And so I started thinking,
well, what are the intersections

00:14:04.710 --> 00:14:06.010
between Latino activism

00:14:06.010 --> 00:14:08.000
and African American
activism in the '60s?

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.540
This is not something
we're usually told.

00:14:11.540 --> 00:14:16.050
They're stories that are siloed
in many ways, narratives that --

00:14:16.050 --> 00:14:18.550
we talk about the Chicano
Movement or the war --

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:20.530
the anti-war movement
or the women's movement

00:14:20.530 --> 00:14:22.860
or civil rights, but what
are the intersections

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:24.160
between all of these things?

00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:27.440
And so that's how I got to the
book that I ended up writing

00:14:27.440 --> 00:14:30.810
that focuses not just on
the Poor People's Campaign,

00:14:30.810 --> 00:14:32.440
although that's the core of it,

00:14:32.440 --> 00:14:38.780
black brown coalition
building more generally.

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:40.080
And the -- yeah.

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:41.970
The opportunities
there, the potential,

00:14:41.970 --> 00:14:44.670
but also the obstacles to
that kind of organizing,

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:47.310
Caesar Chavez and Martin
Luther King Jr. often talked

00:14:47.310 --> 00:14:50.220
about in the same breath,
but they never met.

00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:53.260
They interacted a couple times
through telegram and support

00:14:53.260 --> 00:14:55.970
of each other but they were
supposed to meet in March

00:14:55.970 --> 00:15:00.470
of 1968, which was cancelled
because of the fast --

00:15:00.470 --> 00:15:03.450
the famous fast, of course,
that Caesar Chavez had

00:15:03.450 --> 00:15:09.020
and he was recovering in March,
as well as a cancellation

00:15:09.020 --> 00:15:10.940
by Dr. King, who ended up going

00:15:10.940 --> 00:15:15.810
to Memphis instead
in mid-march in '68.

00:15:15.810 --> 00:15:20.080
So that's how I came
to the campaign first,

00:15:20.080 --> 00:15:23.580
and because the campaign was
not just black and white,

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:27.320
it was Mexican American
and Puerto Rican

00:15:27.320 --> 00:15:30.370
and Native American,
even Asian American.

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:34.740
And so -- and that was not how
the story had often been told.

00:15:34.740 --> 00:15:37.780
It really was a story
that had been told really

00:15:37.780 --> 00:15:42.650
as a black civil rights
campaign and something

00:15:42.650 --> 00:15:47.560
that didn't really work
partially because --

00:15:47.560 --> 00:15:51.130
mostly because Dr. King
had been assassinated.

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:54.420
So there are several
arguments I make in the book.

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:59.240
I'll just go through them very
quickly as part of the framing.

00:15:59.240 --> 00:16:01.570
One was that the campaign
is worth exploring.

00:16:01.570 --> 00:16:04.050
This is something that's worth
rehabilitating to talk about.

00:16:04.050 --> 00:16:06.220
It may not have been
some grand success.

00:16:06.220 --> 00:16:09.510
Those who do write about it
and talk about it in terms

00:16:09.510 --> 00:16:11.560
of failure, and I'll
get to that in a moment,

00:16:11.560 --> 00:16:15.290
because it didn't
achieve its main goal,

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:17.210
which is a rededication
to the war on poverty

00:16:17.210 --> 00:16:19.490
by the federal government,
which was declared in '64

00:16:19.490 --> 00:16:21.200
but never really fought,

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:23.570
never really funded the
way it was supposed to be.

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:26.740
Most of those resources,
of course,

00:16:26.740 --> 00:16:31.050
so many resources were devoted
instead to the Vietnam War,

00:16:31.050 --> 00:16:34.510
which was, of course, part
of, you know, linking poverty

00:16:34.510 --> 00:16:37.690
and war, that you can't
fight the war on poverty

00:16:37.690 --> 00:16:39.490
if you're fighting
this war overseas.

00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:41.840
And some of those
goals that were part

00:16:41.840 --> 00:16:44.160
of that rededication the war
on poverty that were called

00:16:44.160 --> 00:16:47.070
for was a large-scale
jobs program,

00:16:47.070 --> 00:16:50.340
investing income maintenance
for those who didn't have jobs

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:52.880
but were working perhaps for
something other than wages,

00:16:52.880 --> 00:16:57.230
and other kinds of
solutions to poverty.

00:16:57.230 --> 00:16:59.910
There were a few policy
wins, small policy wins

00:16:59.910 --> 00:17:02.100
that I'll address briefly.

00:17:02.100 --> 00:17:05.390
Another argument that I make,
and it's important to recall,

00:17:05.390 --> 00:17:06.970
is that economic
justice is always central

00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:09.440
to the civil rights movement
and to the freedom struggle.

00:17:09.440 --> 00:17:11.600
It wasn't just about
voting rights,

00:17:11.600 --> 00:17:12.900
as important as that was.

00:17:12.900 --> 00:17:14.200
It wasn't just

00:17:14.200 --> 00:17:16.400
about desegregating
public accommodations

00:17:16.400 --> 00:17:17.990
like lunch counters.

00:17:17.990 --> 00:17:20.410
As Ella Baker says, and
I'll paraphrase her.

00:17:20.410 --> 00:17:21.880
You can't -- you
know, what's the point

00:17:21.880 --> 00:17:23.860
of desegregating a lunch
counter to be able to sit there

00:17:23.860 --> 00:17:26.890
if you can't afford the
coke or the hamburger

00:17:26.890 --> 00:17:28.640
that you can get there.

00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:31.050
It was really about
expanding educational

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:35.220
and economic opportunity
and being able to, you know,

00:17:35.220 --> 00:17:37.480
the chance to make a living
and take care of your family

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:40.710
and be respected in
the work that you do.

00:17:40.710 --> 00:17:43.200
That's why King goes to
Memphis in the first place.

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:44.910
The sanitation strike that's --

00:17:44.910 --> 00:17:47.490
that, you know, started
in early February

00:17:47.490 --> 00:17:51.740
of '68 epitomized the Poor
People's Campaign and everything

00:17:51.740 --> 00:17:53.480
that he was trying
to do with it.

00:17:53.480 --> 00:17:56.420
His aide said, don't go,
don't go, it's a distraction,

00:17:56.420 --> 00:17:59.660
and he insisted on
going because it was --

00:17:59.660 --> 00:18:03.250
how could he turn his back
on that and on these men?

00:18:03.250 --> 00:18:07.830
So as I said, the -- one of
the primary sort of goals

00:18:07.830 --> 00:18:09.840
of the campaign was
jobs or income.

00:18:09.840 --> 00:18:12.310
That was the slogan,
the federal jobs program

00:18:12.310 --> 00:18:14.330
or income maintenance,
but, you know,

00:18:14.330 --> 00:18:19.040
Chicano activists there had
other solutions to poverty

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:22.700
that were around land, control
of land culture and respect

00:18:22.700 --> 00:18:25.210
for their culture
and integration

00:18:25.210 --> 00:18:27.670
of that culture in
school curriculum.

00:18:27.670 --> 00:18:32.160
The Native Americans were
interested in the land as well

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:35.690
and having autonomy
from then that --

00:18:35.690 --> 00:18:37.890
from the federal
government, but also having --

00:18:37.890 --> 00:18:41.150
being respected and having their
fishing rights, for instance,

00:18:41.150 --> 00:18:42.450
respected, which is interesting.

00:18:42.450 --> 00:18:44.830
The Supreme Court just had
a ruling earlier this week

00:18:44.830 --> 00:18:46.130
about fishing rights again.

00:18:46.130 --> 00:18:48.510
This is -- continues to
be an issue about whether

00:18:48.510 --> 00:18:53.050
or not Natives can do what
treaties that they agreed

00:18:53.050 --> 00:18:57.570
to in the middle of the 19th
century are they allowed to do

00:18:57.570 --> 00:19:00.870
that or state authorities
and federal authorities going

00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:04.160
to violate those treaties?

00:19:04.160 --> 00:19:08.120
Native -- as Appalachian whites
also emphasized land often

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:10.030
around environmental
degradation.

00:19:10.030 --> 00:19:13.480
Before we think about an
environmental movement being

00:19:13.480 --> 00:19:15.710
as robust as it is
today, that was something

00:19:15.710 --> 00:19:17.010
that they were talking about.

00:19:17.010 --> 00:19:20.960
So it wasn't just jobs
or income, but you ended

00:19:20.960 --> 00:19:26.320
up having a wide range of
demands and solutions to poverty

00:19:26.320 --> 00:19:28.950
that people brought
to Washington.

00:19:28.950 --> 00:19:32.920
Another argument is just
about the nature of coalition

00:19:32.920 --> 00:19:35.150
and its relation to identity.

00:19:35.150 --> 00:19:38.140
We often use the term
identity politics and it's used

00:19:38.140 --> 00:19:40.610
in the public sort of
lexicon in the negative way.

00:19:40.610 --> 00:19:44.110
And I would argue that, no,
I mean you pretty much have

00:19:44.110 --> 00:19:48.960
to identify with a group or be
part of a group to be able to go

00:19:48.960 --> 00:19:50.870
into coalition in
the first place.

00:19:50.870 --> 00:19:56.670
So perhaps this is mutually and
these are not opposing ideas

00:19:56.670 --> 00:19:57.970
of identity and coalition,

00:19:57.970 --> 00:19:59.270
but they actually
support each other.

00:19:59.270 --> 00:20:02.580
And so, for example, the
Chicano activists who come

00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:08.170
from Los Angeles and Albuquerque
and Denver in 1968 come

00:20:08.170 --> 00:20:11.330
to Washington and they
meet other Chicanos

00:20:11.330 --> 00:20:14.250
but they also interact
with Native Americans,

00:20:14.250 --> 00:20:17.270
African Americans and whites
from the west and elsewhere.

00:20:17.270 --> 00:20:22.810
And what they realize is that
it helps them sort of grow

00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:24.940
in sophistication and the
analysis that they bring

00:20:24.940 --> 00:20:28.670
to their own lives, whether
it's -- it's not just about race

00:20:28.670 --> 00:20:34.160
and ethnicity but also
class and gender and region

00:20:34.160 --> 00:20:35.880
and generation and age.

00:20:35.880 --> 00:20:39.190
And so many of those
folks go back and it ends

00:20:39.190 --> 00:20:43.580
up that the effort -- the
opportunity to go and coalesce

00:20:43.580 --> 00:20:47.100
and work with other
people, okay,

00:20:47.100 --> 00:20:49.230
ended up strengthening
their own movement.

00:20:49.230 --> 00:20:51.360
All the Chicano activists
that I did oral histories

00:20:51.360 --> 00:20:54.950
with for my book,
they all pointed

00:20:54.950 --> 00:20:58.480
to the Poor People's
Campaign and said

00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:04.270
that was an important
instrumental moment for them

00:21:04.270 --> 00:21:05.570
to work with -- you know, to --

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:11.590
when they went home and
continued organizing at home.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:16.020
The last argument I would
say is just to suggest

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:17.320
that social movements
-- we need to think

00:21:17.320 --> 00:21:20.360
about social justice movements
in a slightly different way.

00:21:20.360 --> 00:21:23.340
The success and failure is
not a great way to think

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:26.150
about them in the first place.

00:21:26.150 --> 00:21:30.210
That if we're checking, and
I read the Post every day.

00:21:30.210 --> 00:21:33.440
I live here and they always
have these winners and losers.

00:21:33.440 --> 00:21:35.900
You know, articles
about who won,

00:21:35.900 --> 00:21:38.070
who lost in a particular
political moment.

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:39.370
And I read it and I --

00:21:39.370 --> 00:21:42.480
but I always think that's just
not a productive way to think

00:21:42.480 --> 00:21:46.310
about life probably, but
certainly social movements,

00:21:46.310 --> 00:21:49.920
because just because the policy
goal hasn't been achieved

00:21:49.920 --> 00:21:51.550
doesn't mean something
hasn't been achieved

00:21:51.550 --> 00:21:53.210
in the process, right?

00:21:53.210 --> 00:21:56.970
So for many folks who
went to Washington in '68,

00:21:56.970 --> 00:22:01.760
they may not have been able --
Chicanos didn't get the Treaty

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:04.070
of Guadalupe Hidalgo, which
ended the Mexican War,

00:22:04.070 --> 00:22:06.240
reopened and renegotiated.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:07.730
That didn't happen.

00:22:07.730 --> 00:22:09.330
What did happen is
that they had --

00:22:09.330 --> 00:22:11.480
they built relationships
with people

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:15.080
that they didn't otherwise
know, they found common cause

00:22:15.080 --> 00:22:19.920
and commonalities with
white Appalachian activists

00:22:19.920 --> 00:22:24.580
and disabled coal miners
who were interested in some

00:22:24.580 --> 00:22:28.370
of the same issues that they did
and Native Americans, as well,

00:22:28.370 --> 00:22:31.490
from other parts of the west.

00:22:31.490 --> 00:22:33.870
So they built relationships
with each other

00:22:33.870 --> 00:22:35.170
that they wouldn't
otherwise have.

00:22:35.170 --> 00:22:39.790
There were some small policy
wins mostly around hunger.

00:22:39.790 --> 00:22:43.360
Greater food distribution
of surplus commodities

00:22:43.360 --> 00:22:46.930
in the hundred poorest
counties in the country.

00:22:46.930 --> 00:22:49.210
Food stamps became cheaper.

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:50.510
Income maintenance

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:53.050
or a guaranteed annual
income becomes more

00:22:53.050 --> 00:22:54.390
of an issue that's on the table.

00:22:54.390 --> 00:22:56.560
Even the Nixon administration
in '69

00:22:56.560 --> 00:23:02.480
and '70 seriously considers
whether or not that is an option

00:23:02.480 --> 00:23:06.370
and that's a way to
address the loss of jobs

00:23:06.370 --> 00:23:07.670
because of automation.

00:23:07.670 --> 00:23:10.170
And so there are some
things that are --

00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:13.100
that do occur on the policy
side, but I would argue

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:16.140
that it's not just about policy
and wins and losses but there's

00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:18.290
about some other
things going on.

00:23:18.290 --> 00:23:22.480
I will also say that that
many people that went

00:23:22.480 --> 00:23:25.150
to Washington were
inspired by what --

00:23:25.150 --> 00:23:28.820
by their experience and then
came home and ran for office.

00:23:28.820 --> 00:23:32.540
Ray Estiorina [assumed spelling]
runs for governor New Mexico.

00:23:32.540 --> 00:23:35.760
Many other people,
Peggy Terry in Chicago,

00:23:35.760 --> 00:23:39.840
Flo Er [assumed spelling]
in Seattle go home and run

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:42.000
for office, become --
you know, say, well,

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:45.920
maybe electoral politics
has to be part of this.

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:47.350
It shouldn't be all
of it and I make --

00:23:47.350 --> 00:23:49.900
that's my argument
in my second book is

00:23:49.900 --> 00:23:52.710
that electoral politics it's
not a silver bullet either,

00:23:52.710 --> 00:23:57.400
but that maybe both things
are actually part of the mix.

00:23:57.400 --> 00:24:03.330
So I'll end with just a few sort
of broader questions, I guess,

00:24:03.330 --> 00:24:04.630
and things to think about.

00:24:04.630 --> 00:24:06.200
And the biggest one
to me, again,

00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:07.720
is why should we care, right?

00:24:07.720 --> 00:24:09.050
I mean, I'm a historian.

00:24:09.050 --> 00:24:13.910
I write about things that
I think are important

00:24:13.910 --> 00:24:16.970
to not just understand in the
past but understand today.

00:24:16.970 --> 00:24:18.490
That's why historians
do what we do.

00:24:18.490 --> 00:24:20.570
That's why we do what we do.

00:24:20.570 --> 00:24:25.300
So, you know, why should
we care about this moment?

00:24:25.300 --> 00:24:29.780
What are the lessons that we can
learn from '68 and '69 and '70

00:24:29.780 --> 00:24:33.110
and onward for organizing today?

00:24:33.110 --> 00:24:35.300
We are not -- this is not 1968.

00:24:35.300 --> 00:24:37.720
We don't have the same kind of
administration, the same kind

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:40.820
of Congress, even the same
kinds of ways of communicating

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:42.240
with each other, right?

00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:44.490
Social media is both a
blessing and a curse.

00:24:44.490 --> 00:24:49.910
And so what's -- what
can we make of --

00:24:49.910 --> 00:24:51.590
what sense can we make of that?

00:24:51.590 --> 00:24:55.080
Another important one, and
one I wish I dealt with more

00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:57.530
in my book, and I think a lot
of the folks on the panel here

00:24:57.530 --> 00:24:59.820
and the next panel will
talk about a lot more,

00:24:59.820 --> 00:25:01.210
is this role of culture.

00:25:01.210 --> 00:25:06.200
I dabble with culture and
talk about it a little bit,

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:09.260
but I think a more robust
discussion of, is it a barrier?

00:25:09.260 --> 00:25:10.630
A bridge? Both?

00:25:10.630 --> 00:25:13.880
What role does culture play
in bringing people together

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:19.210
and how do we translate
that into politics?

00:25:19.210 --> 00:25:24.220
Culture is politics but into
the policy-making sort of realm.

00:25:24.220 --> 00:25:27.260
And, lastly, what do we
make of the relationship

00:25:27.260 --> 00:25:29.210
between coalition and identity?

00:25:29.210 --> 00:25:32.320
You know, is it -- is identity
politics like a negative thing?

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:33.620
I don't think it is.

00:25:33.620 --> 00:25:37.950
I think it's actually very
healthy because I think it leads

00:25:37.950 --> 00:25:42.990
to other -- eventually it
leads to coalition inherently.

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:45.010
So thank you so much.

00:25:45.010 --> 00:25:46.890
[ Applause ]

00:25:46.890 --> 00:25:48.390
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
Thank you, Gordon.

00:25:48.390 --> 00:25:51.590
Lenneal Henderson, and I think
I had a PowerPoint somewhere,

00:25:51.590 --> 00:25:54.130
but didn't come up.

00:25:54.130 --> 00:25:55.430
Okay. All right.

00:25:55.430 --> 00:25:56.730
So I'll wing it.

00:25:56.730 --> 00:25:58.170
Okay. Thank you.

00:25:58.170 --> 00:25:59.470
Thank you very much.

00:25:59.470 --> 00:26:02.340
I think the inspiration
for our participation

00:26:02.340 --> 00:26:03.780
in the Poor People's
Campaign came

00:26:03.780 --> 00:26:07.220
from Martin Luther King himself
who came to the University

00:26:07.220 --> 00:26:08.570
of California at
Berkeley where I was

00:26:08.570 --> 00:26:09.870
in school as an undergraduate.

00:26:09.870 --> 00:26:12.190
And he came specifically

00:26:12.190 --> 00:26:14.530
to recruit some people
for this campaign.

00:26:14.530 --> 00:26:17.530
And we were impressed by the
fact that he was so short.

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:21.230
We expected a James
Earl Jones sized guy

00:26:21.230 --> 00:26:24.240
and that he was a brilliant
theologian and tactician,

00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:27.140
but he also was a
brilliant pool player

00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:29.070
and he beat us to
death and pool.

00:26:29.070 --> 00:26:33.730
And he used that to recruit
young men from -- to his church.

00:26:33.730 --> 00:26:36.300
He said, "If I beat you at
pool, you got to come to church

00:26:36.300 --> 00:26:40.000
and we're going to put a suit
on you and put you up front."

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:44.550
So he was the -- a stimulus,
and this is October of 1967.

00:26:44.550 --> 00:26:47.780
And several months earlier, he
had given his famous address

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:51.810
at the Riverside
Church opposing the war,

00:26:51.810 --> 00:26:54.840
an address that was actually
written by Vincent Harding.

00:26:54.840 --> 00:26:58.670
But he too -- just to underscore
what Gordon mentioned,

00:26:58.670 --> 00:27:02.240
mentioned his connection between
our protests against the war,

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:08.020
specifically the Vietnam War,
and conscription and poverty.

00:27:08.020 --> 00:27:10.180
He also pointed out that
the poverty program,

00:27:10.180 --> 00:27:14.290
which had been enacted
in 1964, under the mantle

00:27:14.290 --> 00:27:18.360
of Economic Opportunity
Act, actually was opposed

00:27:18.360 --> 00:27:22.200
by most mayors, white mayors in
particular, around the country,

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:25.160
and they got it amended in 1967

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:29.090
so that it actually weakened the
maximum feasible participation

00:27:29.090 --> 00:27:32.550
provision which required
one-third of the poor to be

00:27:32.550 --> 00:27:35.350
on the boards of these
community action agencies.

00:27:35.350 --> 00:27:39.520
And it was underfunded, of
course, and so he wanted

00:27:39.520 --> 00:27:42.580
to bring to America's
attention the fact

00:27:42.580 --> 00:27:46.300
that they had a choice
going into 1968

00:27:46.300 --> 00:27:50.680
and a presidential election
to choose a different path

00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:54.900
for America than they
had been choosing before.

00:27:54.900 --> 00:27:59.650
He also was concerned
about the lack of focus

00:27:59.650 --> 00:28:02.580
and the black power
movement on poverty.

00:28:02.580 --> 00:28:06.090
It was on power but not
necessarily on poverty

00:28:06.090 --> 00:28:09.960
and that was kind of ironic
because part of his reason

00:28:09.960 --> 00:28:12.840
for coming to Berkeley was
to recruit young people

00:28:12.840 --> 00:28:17.750
who he felt had to replenish
the aging generation,

00:28:17.750 --> 00:28:21.040
the previous generation in
the civil rights movement

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:23.450
and the Poor People's Campaign.

00:28:23.450 --> 00:28:27.020
And so part of his purpose was
to bring some young souls there,

00:28:27.020 --> 00:28:29.130
and through the auspices
of a professor

00:28:29.130 --> 00:28:31.150
on the Berkeley campus,
we got some money

00:28:31.150 --> 00:28:35.620
from the university
itself to send 34 of us

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:36.920
to the Poor People's Campaign.

00:28:36.920 --> 00:28:39.130
We went by Greyhound bus.

00:28:39.130 --> 00:28:41.200
We decided that we
would go two months

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:44.340
or three months before the
campaign actually started

00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:46.760
to see how these
things come together.

00:28:46.760 --> 00:28:51.800
So we actually started traveling
in March of '68 and I diverted

00:28:51.800 --> 00:28:54.680
to New Orleans to see my
relatives where I was born.

00:28:54.680 --> 00:28:57.240
And, of course, on April 4th,

00:28:57.240 --> 00:28:58.890
Martin Luther King
was assassinated.

00:28:58.890 --> 00:29:01.550
So my next act was to
get on the Greyhound bus

00:29:01.550 --> 00:29:03.820
and to proceed to
Washington, DC.

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:07.320
And when I got there, you could
see the flames and the smoke

00:29:07.320 --> 00:29:09.540
from all of the activity
and the rioting

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:10.900
that was taking place
in the city.

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:16.650
We should also remember and
then this year, in 1968,

00:29:16.650 --> 00:29:18.240
as Gordon has pointed out,

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:23.180
we had two Civil Rights acts
enacted, one immediately

00:29:23.180 --> 00:29:26.900
after King's assassination, and
that was the Fair Housing Act,

00:29:26.900 --> 00:29:29.060
and the other was the
Indian Civil Rights Act,

00:29:29.060 --> 00:29:33.520
which covered the rights
of indigenous people

00:29:33.520 --> 00:29:35.600
when they were not
on reservations.

00:29:35.600 --> 00:29:37.990
And those were --
those two were enacted.

00:29:37.990 --> 00:29:41.250
We also had a major Supreme
Court decision in the case

00:29:41.250 --> 00:29:45.980
of Green versus the New
Kent County, Virginia Board

00:29:45.980 --> 00:29:49.950
of Education, which rejected
the Freedom of Choice plan

00:29:49.950 --> 00:29:51.250
of the Board of Education.

00:29:51.250 --> 00:29:54.010
We just had a seminar on that
recently, and I mention it

00:29:54.010 --> 00:29:57.500
because King always made
the connection in policies

00:29:57.500 --> 00:30:04.050
and strategies between poverty,
housing, education, health care.

00:30:04.050 --> 00:30:08.150
He said, you couldn't
just look at the one lens.

00:30:08.150 --> 00:30:09.450
You have to look at the --

00:30:09.450 --> 00:30:12.100
how these multiple
lenses produce poverty.

00:30:12.100 --> 00:30:16.190
And he also emphasized that the
federal government was complicit

00:30:16.190 --> 00:30:18.820
in a lot of the racial
segregation and poverty

00:30:18.820 --> 00:30:21.980
that we were witnessing because
all of the housing laws up to

00:30:21.980 --> 00:30:24.900
that point, especially
public housing laws,

00:30:24.900 --> 00:30:27.320
had allowed local communities

00:30:27.320 --> 00:30:28.970
through their housing
authorities

00:30:28.970 --> 00:30:32.560
to enforce racial
segregation in housing.

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:36.350
And then when we developed the
FHA program, it was mostly,

00:30:36.350 --> 00:30:38.530
you know, blue-collar

00:30:38.530 --> 00:30:42.540
and middle-class white people
fleeing to the perimeter

00:30:42.540 --> 00:30:44.300
of the city or the suburbs,

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:47.420
and very few black people
actually participated

00:30:47.420 --> 00:30:49.860
in the FHA program
in its early stages,

00:30:49.860 --> 00:30:54.040
which reinforced this city
suburban racial segregation.

00:30:54.040 --> 00:30:58.270
The other thing about 1968
that I want to emphasize

00:30:58.270 --> 00:31:00.040
that my colleague Marya
will probably deal

00:31:00.040 --> 00:31:03.350
with in her presentation
is the role of Washington,

00:31:03.350 --> 00:31:06.600
DC itself in the Poor
People's Campaign.

00:31:06.600 --> 00:31:10.140
This is five years
before home rule and so --

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:14.660
and yet the faith
community in Washington, DC,

00:31:14.660 --> 00:31:17.510
the educational community
in Washington, DC,

00:31:17.510 --> 00:31:19.850
Howard University and a number

00:31:19.850 --> 00:31:23.860
of other key black
institutions are very active

00:31:23.860 --> 00:31:26.490
in supporting the Poor
People's Campaign.

00:31:26.490 --> 00:31:27.790
They have students going there,

00:31:27.790 --> 00:31:30.500
as my brother Marc
will talk about.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:33.740
There was actually a University
Center there which was

00:31:33.740 --> 00:31:39.300
to coordinate the activities
of HBCUs who said, you know,

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:41.660
hundreds of students to
the Poor People's Campaign.

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:43.990
And majority institutions
like the one I attended.

00:31:43.990 --> 00:31:46.670
They weren't just
there to be interns.

00:31:46.670 --> 00:31:50.110
They actually did work and they
had to have badges and they had

00:31:50.110 --> 00:31:51.410
to have identification.

00:31:51.410 --> 00:31:55.770
So this was important as a part
of our socialization experience,

00:31:55.770 --> 00:31:59.350
as important as any course
we took at the university.

00:31:59.350 --> 00:32:03.240
And combined with my
mother and father's activism

00:32:03.240 --> 00:32:07.810
in San Francisco against
segregation and against poverty,

00:32:07.810 --> 00:32:11.630
it was part of our
inspiration to get to people

00:32:11.630 --> 00:32:16.180
who were younger than we were
to get involved in the issues

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:19.070
of eradication of
poverty, etcetera.

00:32:19.070 --> 00:32:20.370
King was very astute.

00:32:20.370 --> 00:32:23.290
He said, "Look, some of the
worst segregation I've seen,

00:32:23.290 --> 00:32:26.080
some of the worst poverty
I've seen is down the street

00:32:26.080 --> 00:32:29.000
or around the corner from
major university campuses

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:32.080
in university towns
like Berkeley."

00:32:32.080 --> 00:32:33.390
And he was absolutely right.

00:32:33.390 --> 00:32:36.680
Two blocks from the campus
was McKinley High School

00:32:36.680 --> 00:32:39.880
where they dumped all of
the undesirable, you know,

00:32:39.880 --> 00:32:43.170
students at the high
school level

00:32:43.170 --> 00:32:45.790
and they were mostly black.

00:32:45.790 --> 00:32:47.090
And so --

00:32:47.090 --> 00:32:48.390
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:32:48.390 --> 00:32:49.810
No. I went there -- I went
there to teach actually.

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:51.110
I went there to teach.

00:32:51.110 --> 00:32:52.410
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
Just teasing.

00:32:52.410 --> 00:32:53.710
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
When we came back

00:32:53.710 --> 00:32:55.500
from the Poor People's
Campaign, we decided that one

00:32:55.500 --> 00:32:57.580
of our legacies would be to work

00:32:57.580 --> 00:33:00.550
on something called the McKinley
Project, which is to work

00:33:00.550 --> 00:33:02.890
with those students
at that school.

00:33:02.890 --> 00:33:06.730
And so there are many,
many multiple legacies,

00:33:06.730 --> 00:33:08.400
as Gordon has pointed out here,

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:11.160
and one of them is not only
policy, but all the movements

00:33:11.160 --> 00:33:13.500
that were spawned by the
Poor People's Campaign.

00:33:13.500 --> 00:33:16.370
I remember a very young
Marian Wright Edelman,

00:33:16.370 --> 00:33:19.450
just out of Yale Law
School, just passed the bar,

00:33:19.450 --> 00:33:21.320
Lawyers Committee on Civil
Rights, right over there

00:33:21.320 --> 00:33:24.030
on Jefferson Place, and
she was getting involved

00:33:24.030 --> 00:33:27.000
in the Poor People's Campaign,
supporting their work.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:30.000
And, of course, now she
is the iconic leader

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:31.780
of the Children's Defense Fund.

00:33:31.780 --> 00:33:35.000
And I can name about 15 or
20 different organizations

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.550
that grow -- grew directly
out of the involvement

00:33:38.550 --> 00:33:40.750
of those individuals in
the Poor People's Campaign.

00:33:40.750 --> 00:33:45.160
So the links between 1968
and now are tangible,

00:33:45.160 --> 00:33:47.350
they're strong, and
they're continuing,

00:33:47.350 --> 00:33:51.160
and I'm really delighted to
see under the new leadership

00:33:51.160 --> 00:33:54.470
of our two reverends here,
the new Poor People's Campaign

00:33:54.470 --> 00:33:57.510
and I urge all of
us the support this.

00:33:57.510 --> 00:34:04.250
[ Applause ]

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:05.560
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: I'm Marc
Steiner it's a pleasure

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:08.110
to be here, and I'll
make this brief as well.

00:34:08.110 --> 00:34:12.060
And I was asked to talk about
how I got involved and what

00:34:12.060 --> 00:34:14.330
that moment was like so
maybe hit those two things.

00:34:14.330 --> 00:34:17.050
So in 1968, I had
already been involved

00:34:17.050 --> 00:34:18.350
in civil rights movement
for nine years,

00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:20.040
in the movement for nine years.

00:34:20.040 --> 00:34:22.830
I walked my first picket
line when I was 13.

00:34:22.830 --> 00:34:26.130
At 15, I was arrested and beaten
really badly by the police

00:34:26.130 --> 00:34:28.800
in Cambridge, Maryland
when I was working

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:30.450
with Gloria Richardson
in [inaudible].

00:34:30.450 --> 00:34:34.880
And so I joined the anti-war
movement, was a big part

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:37.280
of that, was part of the
underground that movement,

00:34:37.280 --> 00:34:39.010
making false identities
for people to get them

00:34:39.010 --> 00:34:44.210
out of the country to Canada
and Sweden who were GIs

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:47.090
or people dodging the
draft -- not dodging.

00:34:47.090 --> 00:34:49.040
Refusing to serve in Vietnam.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:52.800
I was drafted in '67 so there
was this sort of that --

00:34:52.800 --> 00:34:55.280
at any rate, that was my
background immediately,

00:34:55.280 --> 00:34:56.900
and so I was in the movement.

00:34:56.900 --> 00:35:02.740
In '68, January '68 I was
in Cuba, and when I got back

00:35:02.740 --> 00:35:04.370
from Cuba, I was
with the students

00:35:04.370 --> 00:35:06.480
from Democratic Society.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:07.780
I got back from Cuba.

00:35:07.780 --> 00:35:11.570
I kind of broke with a lot of
my brothers and sisters at SDS

00:35:11.570 --> 00:35:12.870
at that point because
they wanted

00:35:12.870 --> 00:35:15.380
to overthrow the government,
which we all wanted

00:35:15.380 --> 00:35:17.790
to do back then, and
blow up buildings.

00:35:17.790 --> 00:35:20.030
I said, no, we need to
organize among the poor.

00:35:20.030 --> 00:35:22.850
Then we can blow up buildings
and overthrow the government.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:28.010
And so because we, at
that moment, in 1968,

00:35:28.010 --> 00:35:31.150
if you were in the middle
of things, we had a sense

00:35:31.150 --> 00:35:32.580
that a revolution was going on,

00:35:32.580 --> 00:35:34.820
and we actually thought
revolution was going to happen.

00:35:34.820 --> 00:35:36.420
Here, when you saw
what's happening

00:35:36.420 --> 00:35:39.540
in West Africa was happening
in -- all through Latin America

00:35:39.540 --> 00:35:42.460
and Cuba, the Vietnamese
resistance, the Americans,

00:35:42.460 --> 00:35:44.340
all that combined,
people really thought

00:35:44.340 --> 00:35:45.650
that we were in this moment.

00:35:45.650 --> 00:35:49.540
And so that was very
real for people.

00:35:49.540 --> 00:35:53.890
So but I left because I also
had relations with the folks

00:35:53.890 --> 00:35:56.070
who became the young
Patriots in Chicago.

00:35:56.070 --> 00:36:01.280
And the young Patriots were
an Appalachian white group

00:36:01.280 --> 00:36:03.360
of people, Peggy
Terry, Doug Youngblood

00:36:03.360 --> 00:36:05.430
and others, in Chicago.

00:36:05.430 --> 00:36:08.090
They came mostly from
Appalachian, northern Alabama,

00:36:08.090 --> 00:36:10.830
northern Georgia, the southern
parts the Appalachian Mountains,

00:36:10.830 --> 00:36:14.700
and lived in Chicago and
in the uptown neighborhood.

00:36:14.700 --> 00:36:17.870
And they were the -- what
they organized was tantamount

00:36:17.870 --> 00:36:20.110
to the white version of
the Black Panther Party,

00:36:20.110 --> 00:36:22.650
which was the Young
Patriot Party.

00:36:22.650 --> 00:36:26.970
And so when I came back from
Cuba, and I already been hanging

00:36:26.970 --> 00:36:29.210
out with these guys a lot,
and I loved Peggy Terry

00:36:29.210 --> 00:36:31.130
and she was like a mother to me.

00:36:31.130 --> 00:36:36.230
And so and Doug -- and her son,
Doug, who had been in the Klan,

00:36:36.230 --> 00:36:39.720
as was Peggy's father,
and he had done six years

00:36:39.720 --> 00:36:42.990
in Alabama state
prison for manslaughter

00:36:42.990 --> 00:36:46.180
and was what we called
back in the day one

00:36:46.180 --> 00:36:50.740
of the great hillbilly poets
and was until he passed away.

00:36:50.740 --> 00:36:55.020
And we said about working with
the Poor People's Campaign

00:36:55.020 --> 00:36:56.670
to organize poor
white communities

00:36:56.670 --> 00:36:59.120
to join the Poor
People's Campaign.

00:36:59.120 --> 00:37:01.880
And so we lived in the city.

00:37:01.880 --> 00:37:03.240
I lived in Washington
at that time.

00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:05.930
I had an apartment on
P Street, as I said,

00:37:05.930 --> 00:37:09.530
somebody earlier,
was $90 a month.

00:37:09.530 --> 00:37:13.860
It became one of the rest
centers for the people

00:37:13.860 --> 00:37:17.060
in the movement with the
Poor People's Campaign.

00:37:17.060 --> 00:37:21.200
But so we organized all through
Chicago, Ohio, Appalachia,

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:23.270
getting people to
come in to be part

00:37:23.270 --> 00:37:25.020
of the Poor People's Campaign.

00:37:25.020 --> 00:37:26.320
And think about this.

00:37:26.320 --> 00:37:27.790
Given what we're doing
with monuments now,

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:29.350
which I don't disagree with,

00:37:29.350 --> 00:37:31.860
Confederate monuments I'm
talking about, that the patch

00:37:31.860 --> 00:37:37.930
that the young patriots wore
was a Dixie flag with a fist

00:37:37.930 --> 00:37:42.650
on the dungaree jackets
and leather jackets.

00:37:42.650 --> 00:37:46.120
We flew the Dixie flag
in resurrection city

00:37:46.120 --> 00:37:52.300
in our encampment, and it
was very complex but we did.

00:37:52.300 --> 00:38:00.580
And so that movement continued
after we left in '68 and kept

00:38:00.580 --> 00:38:03.000
on organizing in Chicago and
kept on organizing around.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:04.680
And one of the things
I think is --

00:38:04.680 --> 00:38:06.930
well, I'll get to this
-- that in a minute.

00:38:06.930 --> 00:38:10.610
But so the place itself, let
me give it a little piece

00:38:10.610 --> 00:38:14.020
of history I think is important
that I didn't learn until later

00:38:14.020 --> 00:38:17.910
because when King died, we
were all deeply affected.

00:38:17.910 --> 00:38:21.560
Though I was part of the
movement with Gloria Richardson

00:38:21.560 --> 00:38:24.370
in Cambridge and later in other
places that didn't want King

00:38:24.370 --> 00:38:26.760
to come, we said, "We got this.

00:38:26.760 --> 00:38:28.060
We don't need you here."

00:38:28.060 --> 00:38:31.340
There was a real
split in many ways.

00:38:31.340 --> 00:38:36.260
And it wasn't until after he
was assassinated and I began

00:38:36.260 --> 00:38:38.870
to realize his speech at
Riverside that took place

00:38:38.870 --> 00:38:41.950
that I had read and knew
about and all the other things

00:38:41.950 --> 00:38:44.110
that were going on
connected anti-war movement,

00:38:44.110 --> 00:38:48.160
King began to change
and evolve as well.

00:38:48.160 --> 00:38:50.940
And so when King's
assassination --

00:38:50.940 --> 00:38:52.830
well, maybe I'll
step back first.

00:38:52.830 --> 00:38:54.860
So you mentioned Marian
Wright, then Marian Wright,

00:38:54.860 --> 00:38:56.160
now Marian Wright Edelman.

00:38:56.160 --> 00:39:02.370
So when Peter Edelman and Bobby
Kennedy went to Mississippi

00:39:02.370 --> 00:39:05.110
and all through the
poor areas of America,

00:39:05.110 --> 00:39:06.410
they met Marian Wright.

00:39:06.410 --> 00:39:09.120
And Marian Wright and Peter --
that's where they fell in love

00:39:09.120 --> 00:39:10.650
and then they -- and they went

00:39:10.650 --> 00:39:14.310
to visit Bobby Kennedy
one day in Washington, DC.

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:16.650
And he was swimming in a
swimming pool apparently

00:39:16.650 --> 00:39:19.730
after they had breakfast,
and he stopped and said,

00:39:19.730 --> 00:39:21.660
"What we need is a poor
people is moving in America

00:39:21.660 --> 00:39:24.080
to take over Washington."

00:39:24.080 --> 00:39:27.950
And Marion Wright said,
"That's a brilliant idea."

00:39:27.950 --> 00:39:29.310
The next day, she was
supposed to have a meeting

00:39:29.310 --> 00:39:30.610
with Martin Luther King.

00:39:30.610 --> 00:39:32.920
She did and she said, "King,

00:39:32.920 --> 00:39:35.450
this is what Bobby
Kennedy said."

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:37.290
And King went, "That's
what we're going to do.

00:39:37.290 --> 00:39:38.590
That's where it started."

00:39:38.590 --> 00:39:39.890
Most people don't realize that.

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:43.800
And I've been thinking a lot
about what it would have meant

00:39:43.800 --> 00:39:45.540
if Bobby Kennedy was
not assassinated.

00:39:45.540 --> 00:39:48.130
Even though he was not my
favorite person at the time,

00:39:48.130 --> 00:39:50.920
I've come to respect him
since to understand his --

00:39:50.920 --> 00:39:54.360
also how he evolved and
who he became before he was

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:56.330
assassinated and taken from us.

00:39:56.330 --> 00:40:00.560
And King and Bobby Kennedy
started becoming close before

00:40:00.560 --> 00:40:02.630
King was assassinated.

00:40:02.630 --> 00:40:04.650
Just imagine if Kennedy
was elected president

00:40:04.650 --> 00:40:07.860
of the United States and his
closest confidant was Martin

00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:09.160
Luther King.

00:40:09.160 --> 00:40:11.660
So, for me, that's a lesson

00:40:11.660 --> 00:40:13.450
about what we should be
thinking about today.

00:40:13.450 --> 00:40:17.950
Not what could have been, but
what we can build now, right?

00:40:17.950 --> 00:40:22.350
So going -- so going
back to the camp.

00:40:22.350 --> 00:40:24.590
So I lived in Resurrection City

00:40:24.590 --> 00:40:29.400
and Resurrection
City was a mess.

00:40:29.400 --> 00:40:32.650
It was disorganized and chaotic.

00:40:32.650 --> 00:40:34.650
There's no question about it.

00:40:34.650 --> 00:40:37.180
And I didn't think about this
until I interviewed Maria Varela

00:40:37.180 --> 00:40:39.530
for the African American Museum

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:41.760
in for the poor people's
exhibit here.

00:40:41.760 --> 00:40:46.780
And Maria was a Latina
woman, a Chicano who --

00:40:46.780 --> 00:40:48.260
from Chicago, who was

00:40:48.260 --> 00:40:49.690
in the Student Nonviolent
Coordinating Committee

00:40:49.690 --> 00:40:51.780
in the south for like six years.

00:40:51.780 --> 00:40:53.160
She lived in the
midst of that --

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:57.640
the war in the south
because it was a war.

00:40:57.640 --> 00:41:02.850
And she said to me that
when you think about it,

00:41:02.850 --> 00:41:06.010
the men around King
were suffering

00:41:06.010 --> 00:41:07.790
from post-traumatic stress.

00:41:07.790 --> 00:41:09.510
We all were in the
civil rights movement.

00:41:09.510 --> 00:41:11.580
Anybody who walked within the
civil rights movement suffered

00:41:11.580 --> 00:41:13.110
from that because, you know, you
didn't know if you were going

00:41:13.110 --> 00:41:16.860
to live or die every day and you
were beaten severely by police.

00:41:16.860 --> 00:41:19.060
It was not a joke.

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:23.520
And so they saw the man
who was their leader gunned

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:25.990
down in front of them,
beaten to death on a balcony,

00:41:25.990 --> 00:41:28.610
and then they took
up the mantle to try

00:41:28.610 --> 00:41:32.380
to create Resurrection City
and the Poor People's Campaign.

00:41:32.380 --> 00:41:34.660
King's idea for that campaign
was there should be massive

00:41:34.660 --> 00:41:37.220
civil disobedience all
through Washington.

00:41:37.220 --> 00:41:38.850
Take over the city
and shut it down,

00:41:38.850 --> 00:41:40.980
which is what --
that was his idea.

00:41:40.980 --> 00:41:45.540
So it was a very chaotic time.

00:41:45.540 --> 00:41:47.270
So the camp itself was a mess.

00:41:47.270 --> 00:41:51.150
I mean, to live in and the
mud and everything else.

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:53.160
But it's like Jean T. O'Hara
[assumed spelling] said --

00:41:53.160 --> 00:41:56.000
I love the type something
[inaudible] for a book,

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.480
which is -- it was -- let
me get this right because.

00:41:58.480 --> 00:42:02.370
It was terrible and beautiful,
the civil rights movement,

00:42:02.370 --> 00:42:03.790
because it was terrible
and beautiful,

00:42:03.790 --> 00:42:05.970
as a movement always is.

00:42:05.970 --> 00:42:11.690
And so like when the --
when the Latinos arrived

00:42:11.690 --> 00:42:13.510
from the West Coast, there
was no place for them

00:42:13.510 --> 00:42:16.130
in Resurrection City, so they
moved to Hawthorne School,

00:42:16.130 --> 00:42:17.730
which is where they lived.

00:42:17.730 --> 00:42:20.830
Now, Latinos and some black
folks, some white folks,

00:42:20.830 --> 00:42:24.530
and some Native folks live there
and the Native contingents came,

00:42:24.530 --> 00:42:26.000
they ended up in
Episcopal housing

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:27.300
and did not really live --

00:42:27.300 --> 00:42:29.320
most of them did not live
in Resurrection City,

00:42:29.320 --> 00:42:31.110
which is mostly blacks
and whites.

00:42:31.110 --> 00:42:32.570
And some -- and Puerto Ricans.

00:42:32.570 --> 00:42:33.870
It was -- so it was a very --

00:42:33.870 --> 00:42:35.240
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler:
Some Native Americans.

00:42:35.240 --> 00:42:37.330
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: Some Native
Americans but most of them were

00:42:37.330 --> 00:42:39.050
in the Episcopal house.

00:42:39.050 --> 00:42:40.930
And so I'm just saying
this so there was --

00:42:40.930 --> 00:42:43.060
there was real separate
things were going on

00:42:43.060 --> 00:42:44.790
and it wasn't coordinated
well at all.

00:42:44.790 --> 00:42:48.310
As a matter of fact, there was
a time when we actually stormed

00:42:48.310 --> 00:42:51.120
into the hotel where Abernathy

00:42:51.120 --> 00:42:54.800
and those folks were
staying -- you were there.

00:42:54.800 --> 00:42:57.320
So we stormed into the hotel.

00:42:57.320 --> 00:42:58.620
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
Good steak.

00:42:58.620 --> 00:43:00.230
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: Right, exactly.

00:43:00.230 --> 00:43:01.840
So we're eating --
you know, in the --

00:43:01.840 --> 00:43:03.400
we're in the mud
eating beans and they're

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:07.370
up there eating stake and
so we surrounded Abernathy

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:08.800
and those guys saying,
what the hell are you --

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:10.100
what is this, man?

00:43:10.100 --> 00:43:11.400
You're eating steak
in here in the mud?

00:43:11.400 --> 00:43:13.350
You need to get the hell out of
here and come back in the mud.

00:43:13.350 --> 00:43:14.650
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
That's right.

00:43:14.650 --> 00:43:17.530
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: So we were
pissed and so there was --

00:43:17.530 --> 00:43:20.430
there were all kinds of
divides taking place.

00:43:20.430 --> 00:43:24.310
So having shared that, though,
there was a beauty in the spot.

00:43:24.310 --> 00:43:26.440
The beauty had to do with
the people themselves,

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:29.480
the interaction between the
organizers and poor people,

00:43:29.480 --> 00:43:32.400
the interactions and the music.

00:43:32.400 --> 00:43:35.410
I mean, whether your
soundtrack was soul music,

00:43:35.410 --> 00:43:38.700
whether your soundtrack
was country music,

00:43:38.700 --> 00:43:40.210
whether your soundtrack
was rock,

00:43:40.210 --> 00:43:42.380
whatever your soundtrack was,
there was a power and beauty

00:43:42.380 --> 00:43:45.140
to what that was and we
played it and we danced

00:43:45.140 --> 00:43:48.140
and we ate together and we hung
out together and there was --

00:43:48.140 --> 00:43:50.880
and there was a real
communion going on.

00:43:50.880 --> 00:43:52.670
There's power and beauty
in what was going on.

00:43:52.670 --> 00:43:54.990
And when people left
Resurrection City,

00:43:54.990 --> 00:43:57.860
almost everybody, as
Gordon was alluding to,

00:43:57.860 --> 00:44:00.710
ended up going back
home to organize.

00:44:00.710 --> 00:44:03.910
So even if they didn't have --
even if the goals were not met,

00:44:03.910 --> 00:44:06.400
half-a-million new houses to be
built until poverty was ended,

00:44:06.400 --> 00:44:10.150
35 million dollars to be
invested in ending poverty

00:44:10.150 --> 00:44:14.570
in America every year until it
was ended, guaranteed income

00:44:14.570 --> 00:44:17.780
or a job will guarantee
the income.

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:19.870
Those are some the demands
that came out of King,

00:44:19.870 --> 00:44:21.360
that came out of
Resurrection City

00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:23.360
and the Poor People's Campaign.

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:24.670
Even though they were
met, people went home

00:44:24.670 --> 00:44:26.720
and they organized
and began to organize

00:44:26.720 --> 00:44:29.320
in their communities
building a movement.

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:31.590
And people came back and became
Panthers and they came back

00:44:31.590 --> 00:44:34.680
and they became organizers
in Chicago and San Francisco,

00:44:34.680 --> 00:44:36.770
in Mississippi, everywhere.

00:44:36.770 --> 00:44:39.010
So there was a power
in that, as well,

00:44:39.010 --> 00:44:40.310
and I think there are lessons.

00:44:40.310 --> 00:44:42.610
Now, I'll quote thirty
seconds here,

00:44:42.610 --> 00:44:45.850
that there's lesson
for us now in 2018.

00:44:45.850 --> 00:44:48.560
What the new Poor People's
Campaign is doing is

00:44:48.560 --> 00:44:49.860
really important.

00:44:49.860 --> 00:44:51.870
The difference between today

00:44:51.870 --> 00:44:56.460
and then is what made the
Poor People's Campaign work,

00:44:56.460 --> 00:44:59.090
what made Resurrection City
happened, was because it came

00:44:59.090 --> 00:45:03.290
out of people who are actually
organizing in communities.

00:45:03.290 --> 00:45:06.330
So we were organizing in poor
white communities, we were --

00:45:06.330 --> 00:45:08.670
people were organizing on
the res, people organizing

00:45:08.670 --> 00:45:12.190
in the barrio, people were
organizing in the ghetto,

00:45:12.190 --> 00:45:14.880
as we call our places back then.

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:16.850
And that's what it came
-- and that's how that --

00:45:16.850 --> 00:45:19.430
and that has to happen now
if there's real change,

00:45:19.430 --> 00:45:21.120
because when we see these
numbers that came up earlier

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:24.540
in this film about how many
poor people in America,

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:26.770
close to double that number.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:29.550
We use numbers to define
poverty that we created,

00:45:29.550 --> 00:45:32.870
that were created in the 1960s
to define what poverty means.

00:45:32.870 --> 00:45:34.580
Poverty means something
much different now.

00:45:34.580 --> 00:45:36.150
There are more people
in poverty now

00:45:36.150 --> 00:45:38.660
than those numbers that we saw.

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:40.030
America is on the edge.

00:45:40.030 --> 00:45:41.330
People are on the edge.

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:43.550
It's going to take organizing
to pull people together to make

00:45:43.550 --> 00:45:44.850
that change and that's --

00:45:44.850 --> 00:45:48.150
we can learn that from
our experiences back then.

00:45:48.150 --> 00:45:51.530
That's what young
people are doing.

00:45:55.370 --> 00:45:57.420
So thank you.

00:45:57.420 --> 00:46:00.560
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: This -- okay.

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:05.600
So I'm going to try and give
a broad but brief overview

00:46:05.600 --> 00:46:07.650
of what -- how we've
approached this history

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:10.610
at the public library
this past year.

00:46:10.610 --> 00:46:12.770
I want to start by just
saying that I'm a co-founder

00:46:12.770 --> 00:46:16.400
of Oak Hill Center for Education
and Culture in Baltimore.

00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:18.660
We're located in East Baltimore.

00:46:18.660 --> 00:46:22.070
it's a cultural center and
social movement school and most

00:46:22.070 --> 00:46:25.850
of what we -- our work is
focused on is the role of arts

00:46:25.850 --> 00:46:27.510
and culture and political
education

00:46:27.510 --> 00:46:29.610
in movement organizing.

00:46:29.610 --> 00:46:30.910
So we've been -- myself

00:46:30.910 --> 00:46:34.930
and my collaborators there have
been involved in conversations

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:36.920
around relaunching the
Poor People's Campaign

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:38.800
for a number of years.

00:46:38.800 --> 00:46:43.010
So coming to the DC Public
Library this past year

00:46:43.010 --> 00:46:45.290
and being presented
with the question

00:46:45.290 --> 00:46:48.810
of how the library could
celebrate the 50th anniversary

00:46:48.810 --> 00:46:53.670
of 1968 was kind of a
unique opportunity, right?

00:46:53.670 --> 00:46:59.990
So one of the first
questions that kind of popped

00:46:59.990 --> 00:47:04.070
up in my mind was, what are
the public library's values

00:47:04.070 --> 00:47:08.480
and how can it contribute to
a national dialogue and debate

00:47:08.480 --> 00:47:12.690
around what our values
are as a nation, right?

00:47:12.690 --> 00:47:19.040
So the People's University
Project is --

00:47:19.040 --> 00:47:22.690
it came out of a conversations
with the library foundation

00:47:22.690 --> 00:47:27.030
and we set out to accomplish
a few things initially.

00:47:27.030 --> 00:47:30.160
The Martin Luther King
Jr. Library is closed

00:47:30.160 --> 00:47:34.690
for renovations until 2020,
so we wanted to uplift

00:47:34.690 --> 00:47:36.830
and increase visibility of
programming and services

00:47:36.830 --> 00:47:41.230
of smaller [inaudible] branches,
utilize library collections

00:47:41.230 --> 00:47:43.610
and complementary collections
of partner institutions

00:47:43.610 --> 00:47:47.630
to connect this history to
the context of today, right?

00:47:47.630 --> 00:47:50.990
Emphasize the library's
commitment to the legacy

00:47:50.990 --> 00:47:54.450
of Dr. King and his work
and put the library forward

00:47:54.450 --> 00:47:58.150
as not solely a repository for
information but a potential site

00:47:58.150 --> 00:47:59.450
for cultural production as well.

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:04.110
So the focus on the Poor
People's Campaign became kind

00:48:04.110 --> 00:48:07.390
of an obvious direction to go,

00:48:07.390 --> 00:48:09.640
but then the big question was
how do we -- how do we do that?

00:48:09.640 --> 00:48:11.700
I mean, this history is so big

00:48:11.700 --> 00:48:13.680
of just listening
to the stories here.

00:48:13.680 --> 00:48:16.120
I mean, there's so much to it.

00:48:16.120 --> 00:48:18.700
So we looked a lot at this this
idea of cultural production

00:48:18.700 --> 00:48:21.400
and thought, well, how about
we focus on cultural aspects

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:23.940
of the campaign and
Resurrection City?

00:48:23.940 --> 00:48:27.600
The three that we
identified to work

00:48:27.600 --> 00:48:30.070
with were Poor People's
University,

00:48:30.070 --> 00:48:33.490
which was a political
education university project

00:48:33.490 --> 00:48:37.630
that Resurrection City adopted,
the Many Races Soul Center,

00:48:37.630 --> 00:48:41.050
which I'm going to
explain more here shortly,

00:48:41.050 --> 00:48:42.350
and the Hunger Wall Mural.

00:48:42.350 --> 00:48:46.780
And the Hunger Wall Mural was a
large mural in Resurrection City

00:48:46.780 --> 00:48:49.250
where it kind of became like
a visual kind of soapbox

00:48:49.250 --> 00:48:50.620
where people could
share their experiences

00:48:50.620 --> 00:48:52.390
of poverty and oppression.

00:48:52.390 --> 00:48:54.150
And it was a -- sort

00:48:54.150 --> 00:48:57.220
of a cultural activity
to build solidarity.

00:48:57.220 --> 00:49:02.740
So as we thought about how
these three things might be

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:04.690
represented, it became
really apparent quickly

00:49:04.690 --> 00:49:09.960
that the library itself is
really a people's university

00:49:09.960 --> 00:49:11.260
of its own.

00:49:11.260 --> 00:49:12.560
So we've really made -- we made

00:49:12.560 --> 00:49:14.870
that the overarching
theme for the year.

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:19.540
I want to mention actually
that the more we --

00:49:19.540 --> 00:49:21.780
I think about this, I think
it's important to mention.

00:49:21.780 --> 00:49:25.290
Public libraries are a
really interesting space.

00:49:25.290 --> 00:49:28.910
Their relationship to
poverty is very unique,

00:49:28.910 --> 00:49:32.520
so as we see other
public institutions kind

00:49:32.520 --> 00:49:35.800
of collapsing before us, public
school systems, for example,

00:49:35.800 --> 00:49:38.750
the library often
picks up the slack.

00:49:38.750 --> 00:49:43.180
And working with
public librarians

00:49:43.180 --> 00:49:46.540
around these themes has really
revealed that they do a lot more

00:49:46.540 --> 00:49:48.280
than just how people
check out books.

00:49:48.280 --> 00:49:52.150
I mean, these are essentially
social workers, right?

00:49:52.150 --> 00:49:57.530
So the second cultural aspect

00:49:57.530 --> 00:49:59.330
of Resurrection City
was the Soul Tent,

00:49:59.330 --> 00:50:01.050
the Many Races Soul
Center or Soul Tent.

00:50:01.050 --> 00:50:04.240
We had a sweet scale --

00:50:04.240 --> 00:50:09.260
had a fabricated version
of a scaled-down replica

00:50:09.260 --> 00:50:12.560
of a Resurrection
City tent outfitted

00:50:12.560 --> 00:50:14.250
with audio and video components.

00:50:14.250 --> 00:50:16.340
Maggie's going to talk more
about this in a second.

00:50:16.340 --> 00:50:19.160
But it's currently touring
library branches and sort

00:50:19.160 --> 00:50:22.090
of acting as a representation,

00:50:22.090 --> 00:50:25.660
a way of celebrating the
Many Races Soul Center.

00:50:25.660 --> 00:50:27.570
So before I start this,

00:50:27.570 --> 00:50:31.650
the hunger wall we approached
a little differently.

00:50:31.650 --> 00:50:36.360
Rather than a mural, we were
inspired by a poster project

00:50:36.360 --> 00:50:39.120
by the Just Seeds
Art Collective.

00:50:39.120 --> 00:50:42.920
And they had created
a portfolio of posters

00:50:42.920 --> 00:50:44.970
for the new Poor
People's Campaign,

00:50:44.970 --> 00:50:48.540
so we assembled a group of
artists, a local artist in DC,

00:50:48.540 --> 00:50:53.630
and using those posters,
items from Special Collections

00:50:53.630 --> 00:50:56.280
at the DC Public Library,
Library of Congress,

00:50:56.280 --> 00:50:59.410
and educational materials from
the Poor People's Campaign,

00:50:59.410 --> 00:51:01.310
we held a all-day workshop.

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:03.740
And we worked with those artists
to kind of like, you know,

00:51:03.740 --> 00:51:05.810
explore the history and
think about, you know,

00:51:05.810 --> 00:51:09.260
what could we -- how could
we create a DC portfolio

00:51:09.260 --> 00:51:11.690
of Poor People's
Campaign posters today?

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:13.700
So they created the --

00:51:13.700 --> 00:51:18.630
