00:51:21.910 --> 00:51:24.170
The Hunger Wall Poster
Project commemorates the 50th

00:51:24.170 --> 00:51:27.740
anniversary of 1968 and the Poor
People's Campaign, which brought

00:51:27.740 --> 00:51:32.190
over 50,000 protesters to DC
to demand an end to poverty.

00:51:32.190 --> 00:51:35.190
The original hunger wall, the
inspiration for this project,

00:51:35.190 --> 00:51:36.740
was a mural on a plywood wall

00:51:36.740 --> 00:51:39.230
in the encampment known
as Resurrection City.

00:51:39.230 --> 00:51:40.920
We wanted to challenge artists

00:51:40.920 --> 00:51:44.400
to reimagine this
artwork for 2018.

00:51:44.400 --> 00:51:46.280
The artists saw the
importance of speaking

00:51:46.280 --> 00:51:49.190
to the local perspective of what
Dr. King called The Triplets

00:51:49.190 --> 00:51:53.230
of Evil -- poverty, war
and militarism, and racism.

00:51:53.230 --> 00:51:55.330
They made posters on
these topics and the topic

00:51:55.330 --> 00:51:57.210
of ecological destruction,
which is a focus

00:51:57.210 --> 00:51:58.920
of the campaign today.

00:51:58.920 --> 00:52:01.090
A second phase of the project
was inviting the community

00:52:01.090 --> 00:52:02.390
to respond to the issues

00:52:02.390 --> 00:52:04.250
of the Poor People's
Campaign at poster workshops.

