presidential candidates

01:07:49.500 --> 01:07:53.650
that showed up, including Hubert
Humphrey and gene McCarthy,

01:07:53.650 --> 01:07:57.750
mostly from the Democratic
side of things.

01:07:57.750 --> 01:07:59.170
But you're right.

01:07:59.170 --> 01:08:02.070
I mean, there were certainly
members of Congress that were --

01:08:02.070 --> 01:08:05.890
that visited Resurrection
City, were very sympathetic,

01:08:05.890 --> 01:08:08.450
and introduced legislation
in Congress,

01:08:08.450 --> 01:08:10.290
of course, as one of them.

01:08:10.290 --> 01:08:14.660
So yeah. There was definitely
-- people were paying attention.

01:08:14.660 --> 01:08:17.700
I mean, it's something else to
think about perhaps going back

01:08:17.700 --> 01:08:21.600
to Resurrection City
briefly is that to be able

01:08:21.600 --> 01:08:23.830
to pitch a tent city
on the mall,

01:08:23.830 --> 01:08:27.630
you have to get the
Department of Interior's okay.

01:08:27.630 --> 01:08:29.850
So they had permits
to do this, right?

01:08:29.850 --> 01:08:34.640
And so you might ask, well,
why would the Department

01:08:34.640 --> 01:08:37.410
of Interior actually okay this?

01:08:37.410 --> 01:08:40.620
But the Johnson administration,
you know, I spent a lot of time

01:08:40.620 --> 01:08:43.480
in the Johnson Library
in Austin.

01:08:43.480 --> 01:08:46.860
All of his aides -- Johnson
was very much opposed to this,

01:08:46.860 --> 01:08:53.350
did not want to -- did not
want this on his doorstep,

01:08:53.350 --> 01:08:57.660
but his aides said, you know,
look back at other moments

01:08:57.660 --> 01:09:01.400
when people have marched on
Washington and pitched tents

01:09:01.400 --> 01:09:04.260
and lived in Washington
and lobbied for things,

01:09:04.260 --> 01:09:08.730
like the 1932 Bonus Army, which
were World War I vets looking

01:09:08.730 --> 01:09:10.440
for their bonuses early.

01:09:10.440 --> 01:09:15.480
They were -- basically, they
were burned out of their tents

01:09:15.480 --> 01:09:21.010
and sent back over the
bridges by no -- someone --

01:09:21.010 --> 01:09:25.190
the army led by Douglas
MacArthur.

01:09:25.190 --> 01:09:29.590
And so they're like, "We don't
want that to happen again."

01:09:29.590 --> 01:09:31.540
So they looked back
at the history --

01:09:31.540 --> 01:09:34.410
we're actually reading
the Age of Roosevelt

01:09:34.410 --> 01:09:35.710
by Arthur Schlesinger.

01:09:35.710 --> 01:09:39.160
And saying, "We don't want
the same thing to happen

01:09:39.160 --> 01:09:40.480
that happened with
the Bonus Army.

01:09:40.480 --> 01:09:42.450
So we're going to
let this happen,

01:09:42.450 --> 01:09:45.900
let folks have their peace,
you know, say their piece,

01:09:45.900 --> 01:09:50.020
and but we can pull the
permit eventually if we want."

01:09:50.020 --> 01:09:51.320
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: And they did.

01:09:51.320 --> 01:09:52.620
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler:
They did on June 23rd.

01:09:52.620 --> 01:09:53.920
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: And then
they arrested everybody.

01:09:53.920 --> 01:09:55.220
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler: Exactly.

01:09:55.220 --> 01:09:56.520
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: Let me just
tag onto what you're saying.

01:09:56.520 --> 01:09:58.620
First of all, I want to
say thank you to you all.

01:09:58.620 --> 01:10:00.040
What you're getting, I
think, is just incredible.

01:10:00.040 --> 01:10:02.240
I just -- it just
really blew me away.

01:10:02.240 --> 01:10:04.980
I can't wait until the
whole thing is amazing.

01:10:04.980 --> 01:10:11.710
But so part of the reason we
have the permit was Kennedy's

01:10:11.710 --> 01:10:13.690
office, is why we got --

01:10:13.690 --> 01:10:18.710
Bobby Kennedy's office is why
the permit was granted, A. B,

01:10:18.710 --> 01:10:22.260
they -- I was there
the last day.

01:10:22.260 --> 01:10:23.780
They did attack.

01:10:23.780 --> 01:10:27.060
They came in with bulldozers
and police and they came

01:10:27.060 --> 01:10:31.530
in because someone had said
someone had thrown some things

01:10:31.530 --> 01:10:35.590
at a police car, other police
cars, which was complete B.S.

01:10:35.590 --> 01:10:39.740
because there was a point
where a bunch of people

01:10:39.740 --> 01:10:45.290
in the camp were actually sent
back to Chicago, put on busses,

01:10:45.290 --> 01:10:49.620
they were members of gangs
who we knew had been paid

01:10:49.620 --> 01:10:53.350
by the police to [inaudible]
trouble inside the camp

01:10:53.350 --> 01:10:55.690
and create problems.

01:10:55.690 --> 01:10:59.010
They were identified
and put back on the bus.

01:10:59.010 --> 01:11:00.310
So that was real.

01:11:00.310 --> 01:11:02.750
So there was a lot of
[inaudible] from FBI

01:11:02.750 --> 01:11:05.250
and the others trying to
destroy what was going

01:11:05.250 --> 01:11:07.490
on inside the camp that was
already self-destructing

01:11:07.490 --> 01:11:10.680
in its own ways, but the FBI
came in and added to that,

01:11:10.680 --> 01:11:12.120
as did the government.

01:11:12.120 --> 01:11:16.040
And then they came
in the last day --

01:11:16.040 --> 01:11:19.470
I remember having this
conversation with people,

01:11:19.470 --> 01:11:21.920
some older people who had --

01:11:21.920 --> 01:11:25.160
my age now, but they
were older then.

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:27.340
Really old people.

01:11:27.340 --> 01:11:31.160
They -- and who had been gone
-- who had gone through the '30s

01:11:31.160 --> 01:11:34.820
and more and talking
about the Bonus March

01:11:34.820 --> 01:11:36.350
that had happened before that.

01:11:36.350 --> 01:11:37.650
And it felt like that.

01:11:37.650 --> 01:11:41.500
I mean, they came in
lobbed in tear gas,

01:11:41.500 --> 01:11:45.220
came in with bulldozers,
began tearing things up,

01:11:45.220 --> 01:11:48.470
arresting people, and I'm --

01:11:48.470 --> 01:11:52.880
it's a moment I will
never forget just

01:11:52.880 --> 01:11:57.200
because there was this young
woman with two little kids,

01:11:57.200 --> 01:12:01.960
didn't know where to go, what
to do, tear gas was everywhere.

01:12:01.960 --> 01:12:05.100
And I remember grabbing
one of her kids

01:12:05.100 --> 01:12:10.500
and putting a mud-soaked cloth
on her kids face and said,

01:12:10.500 --> 01:12:11.800
"Put this on your
other kid's face,

01:12:11.800 --> 01:12:13.330
put this on your face
and grab my belt.

01:12:13.330 --> 01:12:14.880
We're going to get
the hell out of here."

01:12:14.880 --> 01:12:17.160
And we got out.

01:12:17.160 --> 01:12:19.820
And we were able
not to be arrested.

01:12:19.820 --> 01:12:22.970
And but that was the scene
going on all over the camp

01:12:22.970 --> 01:12:24.780
for the few people
who were left.

01:12:24.780 --> 01:12:26.080
So it was the --
they did attack.

01:12:26.080 --> 01:12:31.030
And so you remember, this
is on the heels of the --

01:12:31.030 --> 01:12:37.450
what people would want to call a
riot, a rebellion that happened

01:12:37.450 --> 01:12:39.480
in '68, when King
was assassinated.

01:12:39.480 --> 01:12:42.050
I was living in the
middle of DC at that time,

01:12:42.050 --> 01:12:43.530
and so this was a part of that.

01:12:43.530 --> 01:12:46.860
I mean, it was a -- there was a
continuum in the minds of people

01:12:46.860 --> 01:12:48.690
in the government
about what happened

01:12:48.690 --> 01:12:51.220
after King was assassinated,
what took place

01:12:51.220 --> 01:12:54.640
because of the assassination
and what this movement meant.

01:12:54.640 --> 01:12:57.960
And remember Bobby Kennedy was
killed while we were in the camp

01:12:57.960 --> 01:13:02.860
and they brought -- and
his -- what do you call it?

01:13:02.860 --> 01:13:04.590
What's the word I'm looking for?

01:13:04.590 --> 01:13:06.660
When they stopped with
his Hearst and stuff.

01:13:06.660 --> 01:13:07.960
They stopped outside the --

01:13:07.960 --> 01:13:09.260
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
The motorcade.

01:13:09.260 --> 01:13:10.560
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: The
motorcade stopped.

01:13:10.560 --> 01:13:11.860
Thank you.

01:13:11.860 --> 01:13:13.160
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
The funeral procession.

01:13:13.160 --> 01:13:14.460
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: And they
-- so when they stopped,

01:13:14.460 --> 01:13:15.760
that was a moment that I think
that is important for people

01:13:15.760 --> 01:13:17.060
to remember in history just

01:13:17.060 --> 01:13:18.540
because I had never experienced
anything like that in my life

01:13:18.540 --> 01:13:20.060
at that moment when
that happened.

01:13:20.060 --> 01:13:23.270
And it stopped -- everybody who
was in the camp and even some

01:13:23.270 --> 01:13:25.640
of the folks who were outside of
the camp from Hawthorne School

01:13:25.640 --> 01:13:29.260
and some other places all
stopped and lined the place.

01:13:29.260 --> 01:13:31.680
There was dead silence

01:13:31.680 --> 01:13:37.950
and everybody began singing John
Brown's Body at that moment.

01:13:37.950 --> 01:13:40.780
And it was just this powerful
moment that took place.

01:13:40.780 --> 01:13:43.450
And there were people inside
the government who didn't want

01:13:43.450 --> 01:13:46.300
that stuff to happen so
the permit was denied.

01:13:46.300 --> 01:13:47.730
I mean, the permit was stopped.

01:13:47.730 --> 01:13:50.080
They wouldn't let us
stay and they came in.

01:13:50.080 --> 01:13:51.670
There was symbolic arrests

01:13:51.670 --> 01:13:53.730
but there was also a little
terror at the end as well.

01:13:53.730 --> 01:13:55.880
I just want to throw that
out there, that this be --

01:13:55.880 --> 01:13:58.960
wasn't all hunky dory with the
U.S. government at that moment.

01:13:58.960 --> 01:14:00.410
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson: The
great irony of this, of course,

01:14:00.410 --> 01:14:04.310
was that we had the Democratic
Party convention quote riots

01:14:04.310 --> 01:14:06.450
that took place later
that summer.

01:14:06.450 --> 01:14:10.960
And we also had the My Lai
Massacre and the Tet Offensive

01:14:10.960 --> 01:14:12.360
in the same year,

01:14:12.360 --> 01:14:15.720
which emphasized the
desperation of the Vietnam War.

01:14:15.720 --> 01:14:17.970
So all those things
were happening

01:14:17.970 --> 01:14:20.500
in the same sort
of temporal space.

01:14:20.500 --> 01:14:25.020
And I think the other piece
of this, I think Gordon

01:14:25.020 --> 01:14:27.570
and Marc mentioned, the
folks who went back,

01:14:27.570 --> 01:14:32.310
think of the number of
poverty program directors

01:14:32.310 --> 01:14:34.520
who ran for elected office.

01:14:34.520 --> 01:14:36.190
I was thinking of
Parren Mitchell

01:14:36.190 --> 01:14:39.580
who had run the poverty
program in Baltimore,

01:14:39.580 --> 01:14:42.520
became our first black
congressman from Baltimore.

01:14:42.520 --> 01:14:45.940
So this spawned a whole lot of
activity in the electoral realm

01:14:45.940 --> 01:14:47.740
that is still with us today.

01:14:47.740 --> 01:14:51.930
By the way, they the new
mayor of San Francisco,

01:14:51.930 --> 01:14:54.270
who's an African-American
woman, London Breed.

01:14:54.270 --> 01:14:57.300
She had been confirmed
as the new mayor.

01:14:57.300 --> 01:14:59.880
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: I think by
some people who's not one of --

01:14:59.880 --> 01:15:01.180
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson:
Its by -- absolutely.

01:15:01.180 --> 01:15:02.480
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler:
I know we want

01:15:02.480 --> 01:15:03.780
to open it up for questions.

01:15:03.780 --> 01:15:05.080
One quick thing.

01:15:05.080 --> 01:15:06.380
I mean, this conversation
has reminded me of is

01:15:06.380 --> 01:15:10.480
that if there is anything that
folks agreed upon that came

01:15:10.480 --> 01:15:15.170
to Washington, was an opposition
to state violence, right.

01:15:15.170 --> 01:15:18.430
And what that -- and state
violence could be both overseas

01:15:18.430 --> 01:15:22.510
and in Southeast Asia but
also here at home, right.

01:15:22.510 --> 01:15:26.930
And so that was the moment when,
you know, folks from across --

01:15:26.930 --> 01:15:30.590
in sort of a pretty wide
ideological spectrum even among

01:15:30.590 --> 01:15:34.280
those who came who were
part of the campaign.

01:15:34.280 --> 01:15:36.930
This was the number one
issue that everyone agreed

01:15:36.930 --> 01:15:38.660
on that needed to stop, right.

01:15:38.660 --> 01:15:42.180
We needed to end the war and we
need to end police suppression

01:15:42.180 --> 01:15:43.780
in poor communities, right.

01:15:43.780 --> 01:15:46.400
Whether it was white,
brown, or black.

01:15:46.400 --> 01:15:47.910
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson: And we had
the current commission report

01:15:47.910 --> 01:15:49.730
also that had come
out the previous year.

01:15:49.730 --> 01:15:51.030
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler: Yeah.

01:15:51.030 --> 01:15:54.200
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: And just a thought
on the, you know, this narrative

01:15:54.200 --> 01:15:56.180
of success versus failure

01:15:56.180 --> 01:15:58.680
of the original campaign
is really interesting.

01:15:58.680 --> 01:16:01.610
It's something that, you know,
the day you're describing, Marc,

01:16:01.610 --> 01:16:03.520
is like, you know, you look back

01:16:03.520 --> 01:16:05.580
at what the newspapers
were saying at that time

01:16:05.580 --> 01:16:07.110
and it says, this is the end.

01:16:07.110 --> 01:16:09.670
The Resurrection City
falls, the campaign fails.

01:16:09.670 --> 01:16:11.460
But that's not really
-- when you --

01:16:11.460 --> 01:16:13.120
it's not really what
happened, right.

01:16:13.120 --> 01:16:16.010
And I think the Poor People's
Campaign today and maybe some

01:16:16.010 --> 01:16:18.760
of the people here who are
from the campaign might speak

01:16:18.760 --> 01:16:21.670
to this a little bit, you
know, is evidence of the fact

01:16:21.670 --> 01:16:25.770
that that work continued
and really changed the way

01:16:25.770 --> 01:16:27.880
that a lot of people would
approach that kind of organizing

01:16:27.880 --> 01:16:29.200
for the rest of their lives.

01:16:29.200 --> 01:16:30.500
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner:
You can't -- see.

01:16:30.500 --> 01:16:32.650
I think that one of the things
that people make a mistake,

01:16:32.650 --> 01:16:35.680
talk about winning and
losing, It -- I mean, to me --

01:16:35.680 --> 01:16:37.320
and I don't want to get
too philosophic about this,

01:16:37.320 --> 01:16:41.770
but to me, just existence
and living in a society is,

01:16:41.770 --> 01:16:43.580
the struggle as part of it.

01:16:43.580 --> 01:16:46.760
And so you know, in existence
is struggle no matter of what

01:16:46.760 --> 01:16:48.440
that made -- wherever you are.

01:16:48.440 --> 01:16:50.590
And so, you know,
people say that like,

01:16:50.590 --> 01:16:52.560
let's say that reconstruction
people say reconstruction was

01:16:52.560 --> 01:16:53.860
a failure.

01:16:53.860 --> 01:16:55.160
Reconstruction wasn't a failure.

01:16:55.160 --> 01:16:56.990
It was one of beautiful
moments in American history.

01:16:56.990 --> 01:16:58.290
They killed reconstruction

01:16:58.290 --> 01:17:01.210
because they didn't want
it to happen in 1877.

01:17:01.210 --> 01:17:03.070
They made sure it didn't happen.

01:17:03.070 --> 01:17:05.770
And so the same thing
with what happened in '68

01:17:05.770 --> 01:17:07.590
but we build on those things.

01:17:07.590 --> 01:17:08.890
That's not the end.

01:17:08.890 --> 01:17:10.190
It keeps moving.

01:17:10.190 --> 01:17:11.680
Who knows what it
means ultimately

01:17:11.680 --> 01:17:13.130
but it just means
that, you know,

01:17:13.130 --> 01:17:16.020
as long as we have a nation
where there's poverty,

01:17:16.020 --> 01:17:18.230
a nation where the racism is
at the root of our country.

01:17:18.230 --> 01:17:21.380
That kind of exploitation
is the root of things

01:17:21.380 --> 01:17:22.680
for many people this country.

01:17:22.680 --> 01:17:24.570
That struggle's going
to continue.

01:17:24.570 --> 01:17:29.160
So it's, you know, it's
-- I'm 72 years old so --

01:17:29.160 --> 01:17:35.120
and people your age, your
generation are carrying it on.

01:17:35.120 --> 01:17:36.530
It's not done.

01:17:36.530 --> 01:17:38.210
We just keep walking on
the shoulders of the folks

01:17:38.210 --> 01:17:39.750
who came before us
and keep pushing.

01:17:39.750 --> 01:17:43.660
And when we push, we get
pushed back and you got

01:17:43.660 --> 01:17:45.400
to keep pushing forward,
you know.

01:17:45.400 --> 01:17:46.700
So it never stops.

01:17:46.700 --> 01:17:48.040
You can't let it stop.

01:17:48.040 --> 01:17:51.450
So I don't get into
failures and successes.

01:17:51.450 --> 01:17:54.220
&gt;&gt; Maggie Gilmore: And on
that note, I love the example

01:17:54.220 --> 01:17:56.660
of the song, Everybody's
Got a Right to Live

01:17:56.660 --> 01:17:59.290
because it's a song
that Jimmy Claire

01:17:59.290 --> 01:18:03.910
and Reverend Frederick Douglas
Kirkpatrick wrote back in 1968.

01:18:03.910 --> 01:18:06.180
And they put together --
they have a whole album.

01:18:06.180 --> 01:18:11.060
You can talk to me at how
you can listen to it online.

01:18:11.060 --> 01:18:12.360
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: Cool.

01:18:12.360 --> 01:18:13.660
&gt;&gt; Maggie Gilmore:
But today they're --

01:18:13.660 --> 01:18:16.720
the new Poor People's Campaign
is using Everybody's Got a Right

01:18:16.720 --> 01:18:19.470
to Live but they've
added a little element

01:18:19.470 --> 01:18:21.480
of hip-hop in that song.

01:18:21.480 --> 01:18:24.610
And teaching people how to
sing it and so it's just,

01:18:24.610 --> 01:18:28.050
I love this example of
the old and the new today.

01:18:28.050 --> 01:18:30.350
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler: Yeah.

01:18:38.040 --> 01:18:40.260
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker: I would
like to hear a little bit more

01:18:40.260 --> 01:18:42.350
about lessons learned
that are relevant

01:18:42.350 --> 01:18:44.730
for what's going on right.

01:18:48.370 --> 01:18:49.670
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson: Well,

01:18:49.670 --> 01:18:52.380
I think one obvious lesson
is persistence, tenacity,

01:18:52.380 --> 01:18:55.790
true press the earth's
going to rise again.

01:18:55.790 --> 01:18:57.370
So it's not over.

01:18:57.370 --> 01:18:59.190
We have to write
the next chapters.

01:18:59.190 --> 01:19:00.690
I think that's what
we've learned.

01:19:00.690 --> 01:19:02.260
We've learned -- I'm
coming back with something

01:19:02.260 --> 01:19:03.560
that Gordon mentioned.

01:19:03.560 --> 01:19:05.200
Policy is one piece of it

01:19:05.200 --> 01:19:09.010
but it's really the
grassroots community organizing

01:19:09.010 --> 01:19:10.750
that makes the change.

01:19:10.750 --> 01:19:13.980
And once the changes are
made you have to keep adding

01:19:13.980 --> 01:19:16.990
because there's always a chance
people dismantle those changes

01:19:16.990 --> 01:19:18.940
as we're seeing in
the court decisions.

01:19:18.940 --> 01:19:20.240
So we're learning these lessons.

01:19:20.240 --> 01:19:24.060
And we're also learning that if
you don't socialize your young

01:19:24.060 --> 01:19:28.080
people at the very early age
to get involved in these kinds

01:19:28.080 --> 01:19:31.060
of activities, they will
be indifferent and inactive

01:19:31.060 --> 01:19:32.620
when they become adults.

01:19:32.620 --> 01:19:35.080
And those are some things that
just sort of stood out for me

01:19:35.080 --> 01:19:38.240
about this experience.

01:19:38.240 --> 01:19:41.530
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: And to
add onto that I would say

01:19:41.530 --> 01:19:43.470
that a similar system
[inaudible]

01:19:43.470 --> 01:19:46.080
to my 22-year-old self.

01:19:46.080 --> 01:19:52.500
But you know, I would just
say it played right out here.

01:19:52.500 --> 01:19:54.530
Capitalism it, to
me is the problem.

01:19:54.530 --> 01:19:56.320
But we're not going overthrow it

01:19:56.320 --> 01:19:59.220
like we thought we were
going to do when I was 22.

01:19:59.220 --> 01:20:02.090
But we need to organize
and fight

01:20:02.090 --> 01:20:06.410
to contain it before it destroys
us and the rest of the planet.

01:20:06.410 --> 01:20:11.370
And I think that for me, one
of the things that's missing

01:20:11.370 --> 01:20:13.390
at this moment and maybe it's
because I'm not aware of it

01:20:13.390 --> 01:20:15.330
and maybe things are happening
that I'm not aware of,

01:20:15.330 --> 01:20:20.290
which is very, very true,
but it's organizing.

01:20:20.290 --> 01:20:24.040
By that I mean the hard
work of organizing.

01:20:24.040 --> 01:20:27.380
One of the things that came
out of our conversations

01:20:27.380 --> 01:20:29.230
in doing the tapes for the
African-American Museum

01:20:29.230 --> 01:20:32.420
on the Poor People's Campaign
interviewing a lot of folks

01:20:32.420 --> 01:20:35.250
who I know and didn't know
from back in the 60's.

01:20:35.250 --> 01:20:37.670
Was [inaudible] to organize.

01:20:37.670 --> 01:20:40.080
You know, when you have
people in Mississippi

01:20:40.080 --> 01:20:42.330
like Fannie Lou Hamer.

01:20:42.330 --> 01:20:43.630
For those who don't know,

01:20:43.630 --> 01:20:46.170
Fannie Lou was an
incredible human being.

01:20:46.170 --> 01:20:48.730
She was a sharecropper who
became a leader of the --

01:20:48.730 --> 01:20:50.550
the movement of Mississippi

01:20:50.550 --> 01:20:52.520
out of the student
[inaudible] committee.

01:20:52.520 --> 01:20:55.580
And was -- and so she organized
the Mississippi Freedom

01:20:55.580 --> 01:21:00.170
Democratic Party, which demanded
a seat in the 1964 convention.

01:21:00.170 --> 01:21:03.610
I was there at that point
in Atlantic City with MFDP.

01:21:03.610 --> 01:21:05.770
And she was this
force of nature.

01:21:05.770 --> 01:21:08.380
But it wasn't her, it
was the fact that she

01:21:08.380 --> 01:21:11.510
and the people she worked with
were organizing cooperatives,

01:21:11.510 --> 01:21:13.710
organizing resistance
in Mississippi,

01:21:13.710 --> 01:21:15.540
and organizing things that learn

01:21:15.540 --> 01:21:18.240
to the Mississippi
Freedom Democratic Party,

01:21:18.240 --> 01:21:21.430
and led to black political
power in Mississippi.

01:21:21.430 --> 01:21:25.930
And they had a co-opsy
organized.

01:21:25.930 --> 01:21:28.420
In the 60's and early
70's in Baltimore,

01:21:28.420 --> 01:21:31.990
we were organizing co-ops
in people's neighborhoods.

01:21:31.990 --> 01:21:36.360
Food co-ops, tenants unions,
striking against landlords,

01:21:36.360 --> 01:21:38.960
people actually actively
building things.

01:21:38.960 --> 01:21:41.450
That's what it takes to
build a movement that ties

01:21:41.450 --> 01:21:43.330
into electoral politics as well.

01:21:43.330 --> 01:21:44.630
You know, they're not separate.

01:21:44.630 --> 01:21:46.040
You have a base to work from.

01:21:46.040 --> 01:21:49.330
And I think that --
and you're seeing --

01:21:49.330 --> 01:21:51.330
there's an energy
out of here now

01:21:51.330 --> 01:21:53.320
as I've not seen
before in a long time.

01:21:53.320 --> 01:21:55.920
The Poor People's
Campaign is taking place.

01:21:55.920 --> 01:21:57.950
All the young progressive
politicians

01:21:57.950 --> 01:22:00.420
of America being
elected across America.

01:22:00.420 --> 01:22:01.720
They're coming from a base

01:22:01.720 --> 01:22:03.270
of work they're doing
in communities.

01:22:03.270 --> 01:22:04.570
So there is something.

01:22:04.570 --> 01:22:07.360
We're just not -- we have to
be aware that it's happening.

01:22:07.360 --> 01:22:08.660
But I think that, you
know -- so it's --

01:22:08.660 --> 01:22:10.280
we have lessons from
[inaudible] --

01:22:10.280 --> 01:22:14.290
people say learn
from our mistakes.

01:22:14.290 --> 01:22:16.250
Everybody makes mistakes.

01:22:16.250 --> 01:22:17.740
Young people are going
to make mistakes.

01:22:17.740 --> 01:22:19.040
Now we made mistakes.

01:22:19.040 --> 01:22:20.340
What does that mean?

01:22:20.340 --> 01:22:21.640
It just means you
keep on rolling,

01:22:21.640 --> 01:22:23.120
you just don't stop, you know.

01:22:23.120 --> 01:22:25.830
So I mean, so I don't like
to dwell on mistakes so much,

01:22:25.830 --> 01:22:29.290
as learning from what you
do and just keep on pushing.

01:22:29.290 --> 01:22:30.590
As the song says.

01:22:30.590 --> 01:22:32.260
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: And
how about leadership.

01:22:32.260 --> 01:22:33.850
I mean, that's a lesson I think

01:22:33.850 --> 01:22:36.540
that the new campaign really
emphasizes this is, you know,

01:22:36.540 --> 01:22:37.840
we have to develop leaders.

01:22:37.840 --> 01:22:39.340
What happens when
the leader falls?

01:22:39.340 --> 01:22:41.300
Who picks up the torch?

01:22:41.300 --> 01:22:44.590
So it's, you know, leadership
development has to be

01:22:44.590 --> 01:22:48.360
at the forefront of
that kind of organizing.

01:22:48.360 --> 01:22:50.370
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: And
when leaders come

01:22:50.370 --> 01:22:51.930
up they will -- they.

01:22:51.930 --> 01:22:53.230
Who's they?

01:22:53.230 --> 01:22:54.530
They can be whatever they --

01:22:54.530 --> 01:22:56.720
that means particular
historical moment.

01:22:56.720 --> 01:23:00.280
But the most effective
people often were taken

01:23:00.280 --> 01:23:02.430
out in the '60s.

01:23:02.430 --> 01:23:06.960
I mean, I don't just mean
-- I mean killed, murdered.

01:23:06.960 --> 01:23:08.260
Fred Hampton.

01:23:08.260 --> 01:23:11.540
I mean, when we talk about
the young patriots in Chicago,

01:23:11.540 --> 01:23:15.250
at that moment when Fred Hampton
was assassinated by the police

01:23:15.250 --> 01:23:18.410
in Chicago, what was being
organized was the young

01:23:18.410 --> 01:23:19.710
patriots, the young lords,

01:23:19.710 --> 01:23:22.110
the brown berets,
the black panthers.

01:23:22.110 --> 01:23:24.290
Organizations -- he
was organizing --

01:23:24.290 --> 01:23:27.980
it wasn't really his idea but
he latched onto another panther

01:23:27.980 --> 01:23:29.810
that came up with
the idea actually.

01:23:29.810 --> 01:23:33.830
But anyway, they were building
was multiracial coalition

01:23:33.830 --> 01:23:37.000
in Chicago and they
couldn't have that.

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:38.360
So Fred Hampton was
assassinated.

01:23:38.360 --> 01:23:41.710
And those things happen.

01:23:41.710 --> 01:23:43.740
And those were real
and we have to realize

01:23:43.740 --> 01:23:48.800
that those things were real and
not shy away from our history.

01:23:48.800 --> 01:23:52.300
And whenever you have a social
movement, once it begins

01:23:52.300 --> 01:23:58.650
to threaten structures
and threaten real change.

01:23:58.650 --> 01:23:59.950
&gt;&gt; Lenneal Henderson: Backlash.

01:23:59.950 --> 01:24:02.440
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: There's going
to be a push back, you know.

01:24:02.440 --> 01:24:05.540
So there was a quiescence
in some senses,

01:24:05.540 --> 01:24:06.990
I think, in our country.

01:24:06.990 --> 01:24:09.300
I mean, people got
elected to Congress,

01:24:09.300 --> 01:24:12.310
[inaudible] black caucus was
founded, you know, and --

01:24:12.310 --> 01:24:15.020
but now we're in a new
stage I think you're going

01:24:15.020 --> 01:24:16.870
to see more young
people being elected,

01:24:16.870 --> 01:24:18.470
more young people
organizing and doing stuff.

01:24:18.470 --> 01:24:20.620
And I just think that's --

01:24:20.620 --> 01:24:23.960
I think we're in an
interesting place, you know.

01:24:23.960 --> 01:24:26.450
I'm not that pessimistic.

01:24:26.450 --> 01:24:28.810
&gt;&gt; Maggie Gilmore: And I think
I've learned that the amount

01:24:28.810 --> 01:24:32.210
of courage that it took to
actually reach across the lines

01:24:32.210 --> 01:24:35.310
of identity to bring
people together

01:24:35.310 --> 01:24:40.080
from such varied backgrounds
and create such a strong force.

01:24:40.080 --> 01:24:43.270
I think we have to be careful
today not to be isolating

01:24:43.270 --> 01:24:44.760
in some of our movements.

01:24:44.760 --> 01:24:47.410
I think, you know,
as a woman I will say

01:24:47.410 --> 01:24:49.440
that the Woman's March
is incredibly powerful

01:24:49.440 --> 01:24:51.640
but it is also isolating
to some.

01:24:51.640 --> 01:24:55.830
So the Poor People's Campaign
is such a good example

01:24:55.830 --> 01:25:05.510
of piecing all of our work
together into one stronger idea.

01:25:05.510 --> 01:25:07.720
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: A new and
unsettling force, right?

01:25:07.720 --> 01:25:09.470
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner: And
Gordon's idea of coalition.

01:25:09.470 --> 01:25:14.620
And one part of that was
reaching across class lines.

01:25:14.620 --> 01:25:17.220
Because there are a lot of,
quote, middle class people

01:25:17.220 --> 01:25:19.630
who were supporting the
Poor People's Campaign.

01:25:19.630 --> 01:25:21.310
And some of them were
black and some of them --

01:25:21.310 --> 01:25:23.700
many of them were white
as those 54 families

01:25:23.700 --> 01:25:25.320
who accommodated folks

01:25:25.320 --> 01:25:27.530
who weren't living
in Resurrection City.

01:25:27.530 --> 01:25:28.920
Who nobody mentions.

01:25:28.920 --> 01:25:31.780
I think we're going to
find some research on them.

01:25:31.780 --> 01:25:33.890
And today the oppression

01:25:33.890 --> 01:25:37.780
of the middle class
threatens that resource.

01:25:37.780 --> 01:25:41.050
Just as Marc was saying, people
are beginning to organize

01:25:41.050 --> 01:25:42.400
from the grassroots up.

01:25:42.400 --> 01:25:44.670
We're now assassinating
the middle class,

01:25:44.670 --> 01:25:47.580
which has been a historical
resource for a lot of change.

01:25:47.580 --> 01:25:51.150
So that's a lesson that we've
got to pick up and run with.

01:25:51.150 --> 01:25:52.770
&gt;&gt; Nick Petr: Yeah I think we
have to remember certain things.

01:25:52.770 --> 01:25:54.280
The things that were in my head
the other day watching these

01:25:54.280 --> 01:25:58.890
children being separated
from their families,

01:25:58.890 --> 01:26:03.580
all I could think about was a
take on the poem from the '30s

01:26:03.580 --> 01:26:07.280
in Germany, first they
came for the immigrants.

01:26:07.280 --> 01:26:08.710
What did you do?

01:26:08.710 --> 01:26:10.290
What we do?

01:26:10.290 --> 01:26:13.940
And so we -- and we talk
about identity politics.

01:26:13.940 --> 01:26:21.160
Sometimes that word is used in a
negative vain but the reality is

01:26:21.160 --> 01:26:26.670
that movements come out of
people, whatever they are,

01:26:26.670 --> 01:26:33.750
who are oppressed as their own
natural movements of survival.

01:26:33.750 --> 01:26:35.540
That's where they come from.

01:26:35.540 --> 01:26:38.910
And they're not to be
condemned, I think.

01:26:38.910 --> 01:26:41.690
This is just -- it's a
reality it's just is reality

01:26:41.690 --> 01:26:43.980
and you've got to
address that reality

01:26:43.980 --> 01:26:45.280
but that doesn't mean
bridges can't built.

01:26:45.280 --> 01:26:46.600
It doesn't mean coalitions
can't be built.

01:26:46.600 --> 01:26:48.190
It doesn't mean people
can't work together

01:26:48.190 --> 01:26:50.280
to make something happen.

01:26:50.280 --> 01:26:52.510
You know, I think that's
something we have to remember.

01:26:52.510 --> 01:26:55.750
I mean, every movement in
the world started that way.

01:26:55.750 --> 01:26:59.130
&gt;&gt; Gordon Mantler: I definitely
think one of the lessons

01:26:59.130 --> 01:27:00.920
from the campaign and
one of the things I

01:27:00.920 --> 01:27:03.770
like about the new Poor
People's Campaign as well is

01:27:03.770 --> 01:27:05.550
that it's not just
about Washington.

01:27:05.550 --> 01:27:08.010
It's not just about coming

01:27:08.010 --> 01:27:10.640
to D.C. That's important
symbolically.

01:27:10.640 --> 01:27:13.150
It's important for, you know,
for bringing people together

01:27:13.150 --> 01:27:17.420
from around the country
for purposes of the media.

01:27:17.420 --> 01:27:21.840
But going to state capitals and
organizing in more local places.

01:27:21.840 --> 01:27:26.180
I mean, I live in Virginia and,
you know, we've seen -- we --

01:27:26.180 --> 01:27:28.310
you know, more progressive
people.

01:27:28.310 --> 01:27:31.120
I'm trying not to get partisan
here but more progressive people

01:27:31.120 --> 01:27:34.260
on this took over the
House of Delegates.

01:27:34.260 --> 01:27:36.640
There's been Medicaid
expansion in that state

01:27:36.640 --> 01:27:38.840
as a result of that, right.

01:27:38.840 --> 01:27:42.850
And so it's not just about what
the federal government is doing,

01:27:42.850 --> 01:27:45.770
right, and I think
increasing increasingly so.

01:27:45.770 --> 01:27:47.200
But what are state
government's doing?

01:27:47.200 --> 01:27:50.420
What our county councils
and the school boards doing

01:27:50.420 --> 01:27:52.490
and courthouses and so.

01:27:52.490 --> 01:27:55.460
So it goes back to this idea
of local organizing, right,.

01:27:55.460 --> 01:27:59.050
So you can come to D.C. You can
be engaged with federal politics

01:27:59.050 --> 01:28:01.240
but you have to also be engaged

01:28:01.240 --> 01:28:03.780
with local politics
as much as possible.

01:28:03.780 --> 01:28:05.990
Electoral and otherwise, right.

01:28:05.990 --> 01:28:08.370
And so I think that
that's one of the things

01:28:08.370 --> 01:28:11.060
that the '68 campaign
didn't do as much.

01:28:11.060 --> 01:28:14.800
It was part of the long
term plan but that got --

01:28:14.800 --> 01:28:16.550
that was something
that King talked about.

01:28:16.550 --> 01:28:18.030
Well we'll go to
Washington and then we'll go

01:28:18.030 --> 01:28:20.690
to the 50 biggest
cities in the country

01:28:20.690 --> 01:28:22.260
and continue to organize.

01:28:22.260 --> 01:28:24.790
Well they went to the
conventions, the Democratic

01:28:24.790 --> 01:28:27.810
and Republican conventions
in Chicago and Miami Beach.

01:28:27.810 --> 01:28:29.910
But that was really --
and there was a few places

01:28:29.910 --> 01:28:33.870
where you see organizing
around the campaign per se,

01:28:33.870 --> 01:28:36.620
many people went back and
did their own organizing,

01:28:36.620 --> 01:28:38.310
not necessarily under
the umbrella

01:28:38.310 --> 01:28:39.610
of the Poor People's Campaign.

01:28:39.610 --> 01:28:44.760
So in a sense it did happen
but not just through SCLC

01:28:44.760 --> 01:28:50.160
but I think that that's an
important point that it's --

01:28:50.160 --> 01:28:51.460
you don't have to come here.

01:28:51.460 --> 01:28:53.220
You don't have to be in
D.C. to bring change.

01:28:53.220 --> 01:28:56.830
In some ways the change really
happens in Lansing and Jackson

01:28:56.830 --> 01:29:01.100
and Albuquerque and so
that's -- and Richmond.

01:29:01.100 --> 01:29:02.700
Those are the places
that are just

01:29:02.700 --> 01:29:04.000
as important if not more so.

01:29:04.000 --> 01:29:06.300
So.

01:29:11.310 --> 01:29:13.760
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker: I
wanted to ask you, Maggie,

01:29:13.760 --> 01:29:17.390
how the materials digitized

01:29:17.390 --> 01:29:24.440
by the D.C. Public Library are
available to the broad public.

01:29:24.440 --> 01:29:25.740
&gt;&gt; Maggie Gilmore: Sure.

01:29:25.740 --> 01:29:29.600
Digdc.dclibrary.org and you
don't need a library card

01:29:29.600 --> 01:29:31.900
to log in.

01:29:34.230 --> 01:29:35.530
&gt;&gt; Marc Steiner:
That's important.

01:29:35.530 --> 01:29:36.870
&gt;&gt; Maggie Gilmore:
And there is --

01:29:36.870 --> 01:29:40.460
you'll see there is a Poor
People's Campaign collection

01:29:40.460 --> 01:29:43.590
where, you know,
again or another point

01:29:43.590 --> 01:29:44.890
to what we have learned.

01:29:44.890 --> 01:29:47.060
You can actually look
at some of the documents

01:29:47.060 --> 01:29:51.710
and see the language that
was used in lobbying Congress

01:29:51.710 --> 01:29:56.460
and the different locations that
they were going to and targeting

01:29:56.460 --> 01:29:59.950
and some of the requests
and the demands

01:29:59.950 --> 01:30:03.630
that were being made
at that time.

01:30:03.630 --> 01:30:05.710
&gt;&gt; Anna Yaga: Does this work?

01:30:05.710 --> 01:30:08.850
Oh here we go.

01:30:08.850 --> 01:30:10.740
My name is Anna Yaga [assumed
spelling] I'm an artist

01:30:10.740 --> 01:30:12.430
in residence with the
D.C. Public Library

01:30:12.430 --> 01:30:15.440
so I'm working closely
with Maggie and Nick.

01:30:15.440 --> 01:30:17.860
And also with the Poor
People's Campaign.

01:30:17.860 --> 01:30:23.170
And you know, one of the things
that strikes me now, I mean,

01:30:23.170 --> 01:30:24.610
you speak about this
attempt, you know,

01:30:24.610 --> 01:30:27.770
this attempted assassination
of the middle class.

01:30:27.770 --> 01:30:31.790
And I just want to share
something that's been tumbling

01:30:31.790 --> 01:30:36.620
and like this foundation or
these identities of around class

01:30:36.620 --> 01:30:39.760
that have really been
smashed and disrupted.

01:30:39.760 --> 01:30:43.890
And you know, for me --
and I ended up speaking.

01:30:43.890 --> 01:30:47.140
I ended up testifying last
couple weeks ago on the right

01:30:47.140 --> 01:30:48.680
to health care and
a healthy planet.

01:30:48.680 --> 01:30:52.180
And you know, I just want
to put out there that I came

01:30:52.180 --> 01:30:55.670
to this movement work
thinking of myself as an ally.

01:30:55.670 --> 01:30:59.670
And I feel like this idea of
the middle class is such a lie

01:30:59.670 --> 01:31:02.490
and an illusion because,
you know,

01:31:02.490 --> 01:31:03.830
you're just a few
more paychecks away

01:31:03.830 --> 01:31:05.340
from being out on the street.

01:31:05.340 --> 01:31:08.780
And you know, when I was
organizing in public housing,

01:31:08.780 --> 01:31:11.140
Miss Mary, who was
like the local profit,

01:31:11.140 --> 01:31:13.810
she would say that same thing.

01:31:13.810 --> 01:31:16.510
That if you make
$60,000, you know.

01:31:16.510 --> 01:31:19.480
And I understand that -- I
understood it intellectually,

01:31:19.480 --> 01:31:24.150
right, but it wasn't until I had
lost my housing, my health care,

01:31:24.150 --> 01:31:27.010
my income all in
one month, right.

01:31:27.010 --> 01:31:31.100
And that the kind of pinnacle
of a number of experiences

01:31:31.100 --> 01:31:32.870
like even before that.

01:31:32.870 --> 01:31:36.310
Finding a letter on the house
that I lived in that said

01:31:36.310 --> 01:31:38.690
that the police are
coming to get your things,

01:31:38.690 --> 01:31:42.140
you have 30 days to get out
it was an illegal eviction.

01:31:42.140 --> 01:31:43.550
It didn't make, you
know -- and that was --

01:31:43.550 --> 01:31:46.040
the landlord basically
had been going

01:31:46.040 --> 01:31:48.280
through foreclosure
and didn't tell us.

01:31:48.280 --> 01:31:51.670
And so all of these different
experiences culminating

01:31:51.670 --> 01:31:54.980
in me coming to the very people
that I was, had been organizing

01:31:54.980 --> 01:31:57.110
within public housing
saying what do I do

01:31:57.110 --> 01:31:59.000
because it had happened
to them first.

01:31:59.000 --> 01:32:02.290
And so I feel like in this
attempted assassination

01:32:02.290 --> 01:32:06.450
where it's also an opportunity,
it's an invitation for people

01:32:06.450 --> 01:32:09.250
to really like, let
the lies shed

01:32:09.250 --> 01:32:11.880
so that we can actually
come together.

01:32:11.880 --> 01:32:17.270
And I just want to share that
as a way to kind of offer,

01:32:17.270 --> 01:32:21.880
you know, it's one thing
to speak about something

