02:00:01.370 --> 02:00:05.840
And the others, I hadn't
realized how much had come

02:00:05.840 --> 02:00:08.400
out of Resurrection City one.

02:00:08.400 --> 02:00:11.450
How many people had gone
on to so many things

02:00:11.450 --> 02:00:13.190
and I'm very heartened by that

02:00:13.190 --> 02:00:18.420
and I hope similar thing has
happen with this one as well.

02:00:18.420 --> 02:00:22.090
I want to begin with
just a word of context

02:00:22.090 --> 02:00:24.810
because Resurrection
City didn't just happen

02:00:24.810 --> 02:00:28.380
on it's own it didn't
just happen

02:00:28.380 --> 02:00:31.220
because Bobby Kennedy
made a suggestion.

02:00:31.220 --> 02:00:33.870
The older people in
the room know this,

02:00:33.870 --> 02:00:35.170
what I'm about to say.

02:00:35.170 --> 02:00:41.280
In 1960 there were sit
in at lunch counters.

02:00:41.280 --> 02:00:47.820
In 1961 white and black people
rode buses into the south.

02:00:47.820 --> 02:00:49.120
The buses who burned.

02:00:49.120 --> 02:00:50.590
They were beaten in jailed.

02:00:50.590 --> 02:00:56.250
In 1963 a church in
Birmingham was blown up.

02:00:56.250 --> 02:00:58.980
I Have a Dream speech happened.

02:00:58.980 --> 02:01:05.280
1965 was Selma.

02:01:05.280 --> 02:01:06.580
There was violence.

02:01:06.580 --> 02:01:07.880
There was risk.

02:01:07.880 --> 02:01:10.280
There was danger and it
was work over many years.

02:01:10.280 --> 02:01:12.990
The people who put
together Resurrection City,

02:01:12.990 --> 02:01:14.850
they had been through much that.

02:01:14.850 --> 02:01:18.470
They had seen their
friends, as you said, killed.

02:01:18.470 --> 02:01:22.810
Many of them had been beaten.

02:01:22.810 --> 02:01:25.110
We had [inaudible] --

02:01:28.080 --> 02:01:31.320
We all had these little badges

02:01:31.320 --> 02:01:35.550
and on the badges it
had our blood type.

02:01:35.550 --> 02:01:37.550
Now I've been involved
in a lot of things

02:01:37.550 --> 02:01:39.360
but I've never been
involved in a thing

02:01:39.360 --> 02:01:41.340
where they put your
blood type on it.

02:01:41.340 --> 02:01:43.330
The reason they put your
blood type on it was

02:01:43.330 --> 02:01:46.260
because the people who organized
it had been in things were a lot

02:01:46.260 --> 02:01:50.270
of them had been carted off
to the hospital [inaudible].

02:01:50.270 --> 02:01:51.770
And -- is that me?

02:01:51.770 --> 02:01:53.070
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
I think so.

02:01:53.070 --> 02:01:55.650
&gt;&gt; Bruce Jackson:
And at the beginning

02:01:55.650 --> 02:01:59.230
of Resurrection City
there's a lot of optimism

02:01:59.230 --> 02:02:01.810
but nobody knew what
was going happen.

02:02:01.810 --> 02:02:04.600
There was a permit but
nobody knew how long

02:02:04.600 --> 02:02:06.260
that was going to stand.

02:02:06.260 --> 02:02:09.240
There had been many other things
for which there been permits

02:02:09.240 --> 02:02:12.490
and things had been
disrupted violently.

02:02:12.490 --> 02:02:16.650
So there was optimism, joy, and
a great feeling of cooperation

02:02:16.650 --> 02:02:20.930
but there was also an awareness
of the world who were living in.

02:02:20.930 --> 02:02:23.110
And that was a part of
what it was all about.

02:02:23.110 --> 02:02:27.070
I got involved in it because
of a guy named Ralph Rinzler

02:02:27.070 --> 02:02:29.340
who some of you who
worked with the library

02:02:29.340 --> 02:02:32.000
or the Smithsonian may know.

02:02:32.000 --> 02:02:36.390
Ralph eventually became deputy
director of the Smithsonian

02:02:36.390 --> 02:02:37.690
or something like that.

02:02:37.690 --> 02:02:40.740
He's responsible
for the Festival --

02:02:40.740 --> 02:02:44.490
Smithsonian Festival
on the mall every year.

02:02:44.490 --> 02:02:47.990
I got to know him through
the Newport Folk Foundation.

02:02:47.990 --> 02:02:50.680
I was the director of
the Newport Folk Festival

02:02:50.680 --> 02:02:52.750
and Ralph worked for us.

02:02:52.750 --> 02:02:56.020
He would scout talent and
he would, occasionally

02:02:56.020 --> 02:03:00.610
when we had projects, he would
run the -- not run the projects.

02:03:00.610 --> 02:03:02.490
Ralph wasn't kind of
guy who'd run things.

02:03:02.490 --> 02:03:04.110
He was the kind of
guy who would go in

02:03:04.110 --> 02:03:06.240
and say, "How can I help you?"

02:03:06.240 --> 02:03:09.620
or "I have access
to these resources.

02:03:09.620 --> 02:03:11.500
Is there a way I can
help you use them?"

02:03:11.500 --> 02:03:17.030
And that will figure in the
story I'm about to tell you.

02:03:17.030 --> 02:03:20.400
And he came to us one day,
one of our board meetings

02:03:20.400 --> 02:03:22.640
and he'd been in
touch with SCLC.

02:03:22.640 --> 02:03:27.660
And he said, "One of the
things they could use is a

02:03:27.660 --> 02:03:29.740
music program."

02:03:29.740 --> 02:03:32.730
Because they realized there's
a lot of adults who are going

02:03:32.730 --> 02:03:34.980
to be there who aren't going
to have a lot to do at night.

02:03:34.980 --> 02:03:38.270
And they're are going to
be a lot of kids there

02:03:38.270 --> 02:03:42.230
who aren't going to
have a lot to do at all.

02:03:42.230 --> 02:03:44.150
So could we set something up?

02:03:44.150 --> 02:03:46.190
And so Frederick Douglass --

02:03:46.190 --> 02:03:48.860
Reverend Frederick
Douglas Kirkpatrick,

02:03:48.860 --> 02:03:51.110
who was mentioned
a little while ago.

02:03:51.110 --> 02:03:53.850
Kirk had been part
of an organization

02:03:53.850 --> 02:03:57.000
in Louisiana called the
Deacons for Defense.

02:03:57.000 --> 02:04:01.050
They banded together and routed
a group of white nationalists,

02:04:01.050 --> 02:04:04.800
much to the chagrin of
the white nationalists.

02:04:04.800 --> 02:04:06.100
He was a lovely guy.

02:04:06.100 --> 02:04:07.400
I liked him a lot.

02:04:07.400 --> 02:04:10.200
And he was a Newport
board too by then.

02:04:10.200 --> 02:04:14.050
So Kirk came down, Georgia
Sea Islands singers came

02:04:14.050 --> 02:04:16.560
and we all came down.

02:04:16.560 --> 02:04:20.950
Ralph and I came and we met
with the SCLC leadership.

02:04:20.950 --> 02:04:25.670
When the Newport board decided
to do this, it was a meeting

02:04:25.670 --> 02:04:30.460
at which Alan Lomax, the
folklorist was not present.

02:04:30.460 --> 02:04:35.580
And we were all really happy
about that, because Alan is --

02:04:35.580 --> 02:04:40.060
Alan had a good heart but he
was a pushy son of a bitch.

02:04:40.060 --> 02:04:45.810
And so, so we didn't tell him
we were doing it, and everybody,

02:04:45.810 --> 02:04:49.210
and everybody told
everybody, do not tell Alan,

02:04:49.210 --> 02:04:50.990
you know do not issue
the minutes

02:04:50.990 --> 02:04:52.770
of this meeting, nothing.

02:04:52.770 --> 02:04:57.020
So Ralph and I are meeting
and you'll see some pictures

02:04:57.020 --> 02:05:00.790
in a moment, Washington
is burned out, during,

02:05:00.790 --> 02:05:04.300
it's just desolation, road
to [inaudible] to that,

02:05:04.300 --> 02:05:08.440
that's the LC office was just,
it, it was -- it was like being,

02:05:08.440 --> 02:05:10.430
it was a bombed out city.

02:05:10.430 --> 02:05:12.920
And so we're meeting
with everybody,

02:05:12.920 --> 02:05:16.620
and Ralph is saying how can I
help you if we have this money,

02:05:16.620 --> 02:05:19.830
and we have connections to
these [inaudible], these people.

02:05:19.830 --> 02:05:25.830
And Alan burst into the room
and proceeds to lecture them

02:05:25.830 --> 02:05:28.920
on the importance
of black music,

02:05:28.920 --> 02:05:31.530
on the character of black music.

02:05:31.530 --> 02:05:35.680
And tells them what they
should do with black music.

02:05:35.680 --> 02:05:39.960
And as Alan spoke, his Texas
accent got thicker and thicker,

02:05:39.960 --> 02:05:43.410
which is something he
tended to do I noticed

02:05:43.410 --> 02:05:44.710
when he's with black people.

02:05:44.710 --> 02:05:47.030
And it would start out,
sort of talking like this

02:05:47.030 --> 02:05:49.330
and by the end he's
talking like that.

02:05:49.330 --> 02:05:54.540
And so the room is
getting colder and colder.

02:05:54.540 --> 02:05:57.120
Ralph and I want to
slide under the table.

02:05:57.120 --> 02:06:00.710
We just think we are
dead, the project is dead.

02:06:00.710 --> 02:06:02.800
And it was such a sweet
project, you know doing things

02:06:02.800 --> 02:06:04.780
for your kids is so nice.

02:06:04.780 --> 02:06:10.100
And so Jim Bevel says to
Ralph and me, you guys got

02:06:10.100 --> 02:06:11.900
to do something about that boy.

02:06:11.900 --> 02:06:16.040
[ Laughter ]

02:06:16.040 --> 02:06:19.000
Ralph says, well he means well.

02:06:19.000 --> 02:06:20.560
Bill, Bevel says, yeah.

02:06:20.560 --> 02:06:24.080
So anyhow it all came together.

02:06:24.080 --> 02:06:30.320
It, it, it got fixed,
it, it came together.

02:06:30.320 --> 02:06:31.820
And a while later.

02:06:31.820 --> 02:06:33.120
And I -- after this time,

02:06:33.120 --> 02:06:36.770
I don't remember how many days
later, we went down to set

02:06:36.770 --> 02:06:38.380
up the, for the program.

02:06:38.380 --> 02:06:41.280
And I, I was just there for
the first few days of it.

02:06:41.280 --> 02:06:43.230
So what I'm going to show
you, just some pictures

02:06:43.230 --> 02:06:44.600
from those first few days.

02:06:44.600 --> 02:06:48.840
And then I came back
for the solidarity date.

02:06:48.840 --> 02:06:51.060
And I wanted to say something
about that though, I'm,

02:06:51.060 --> 02:06:53.730
I'm going to hold
that off a little bit.

02:06:53.730 --> 02:06:55.290
That's Ralph.

02:06:55.290 --> 02:06:58.340
And that is a, a
Newport Folk Festival.

02:06:58.340 --> 02:07:01.200
I didn't have any
pictures of him thee.

02:07:01.200 --> 02:07:05.170
And he's the sweetest
guy as, as he looks like.

02:07:05.170 --> 02:07:07.570
This is the photograph
out of the --

02:07:07.570 --> 02:07:09.750
out of the cab window
on the way.

02:07:09.750 --> 02:07:12.630
And that's another
photograph that some

02:07:12.630 --> 02:07:16.510
of you remember walking
and looking at that.

02:07:16.510 --> 02:07:19.140
And this was when
I first got there.

02:07:19.140 --> 02:07:23.390
And those were the first
times anybody ever said to me,

02:07:23.390 --> 02:07:27.230
a guy came over and he said I
keep looking at that and I think

02:07:27.230 --> 02:07:30.700
of a Klansman looking
down at me all the time.

02:07:30.700 --> 02:07:34.550
And I had never looked at the
Washington monument since,

02:07:34.550 --> 02:07:39.200
and not thought of this Klansman
looking down at me all the time.

02:07:39.200 --> 02:07:43.250
And now, you know, it towers
all over that part of the city.

02:07:43.250 --> 02:07:47.650
And there's some
significance in that.

02:07:47.650 --> 02:07:51.060
So it, oh and, and the
first few days it was almost

02:07:51.060 --> 02:07:52.360
entirely black.

02:07:52.360 --> 02:07:54.320
The, the buses hadn't come yet.

02:07:54.320 --> 02:07:57.880
One of the things we decided to
do by the way in addition to,

02:07:57.880 --> 02:08:02.790
it says this music program, was
to document what we were doing.

02:08:02.790 --> 02:08:06.470
So those recordings that
are in the library would,

02:08:06.470 --> 02:08:07.970
we recorded the performances.

02:08:07.970 --> 02:08:12.540
You'll see some newsmen in
a moment, I got one of them

02:08:12.540 --> 02:08:15.600
to give me a copy of all his
tapes of the first meeting

02:08:15.600 --> 02:08:18.580
of Resurrection City,
which was really fiery,

02:08:18.580 --> 02:08:20.080
it was really great.

02:08:20.080 --> 02:08:23.200
Kirk performed, other
people performed afterwards.

02:08:23.200 --> 02:08:27.940
And another folk who was hired
by Newport, Henry Glassy,

02:08:27.940 --> 02:08:32.490
road with one of the bus
trains coming from California.

02:08:32.490 --> 02:08:34.870
And he did interviews
on the way.

02:08:34.870 --> 02:08:37.990
So we had some documentation
to stuff

02:08:37.990 --> 02:08:40.760
that would not, not
otherwise exist.

02:08:40.760 --> 02:08:42.610
And to get another
thing that's pleased me

02:08:42.610 --> 02:08:46.910
about being here today is seeing
how you guys have been able

02:08:46.910 --> 02:08:51.900
to use that material around,
you know, everybody else who was

02:08:51.900 --> 02:08:55.710
on that board with me would
be absolutely delighted.

02:08:55.710 --> 02:08:59.470
Those are the A framed ends
arriving that you can see a lot

02:08:59.470 --> 02:09:04.350
of local volunteers were
involved in that work.

02:09:04.350 --> 02:09:05.870
There were a lot of
people in Washington

02:09:05.870 --> 02:09:09.990
who were helping set
up Resurrection City.

02:09:09.990 --> 02:09:14.770
And you can see its
setting them up.

02:09:14.770 --> 02:09:19.430
And a lot of the A frames had
graffiti on it, but not the kind

02:09:19.430 --> 02:09:22.280
of graffiti you see nowadays.

02:09:22.280 --> 02:09:27.090
It, graffiti, I've
been to the mountain.

02:09:27.090 --> 02:09:29.800
People's names, quotes, there
are a number of quotations

02:09:29.800 --> 02:09:32.440
from Dr. King you would
see, you'd see on houses.

02:09:32.440 --> 02:09:39.020
And I think the names
of some of the people

02:09:39.020 --> 02:09:41.360
in CLC are on that building.

02:09:41.360 --> 02:09:46.210
I always loved this picture,
this guy with his kid just with,

02:09:46.210 --> 02:09:49.800
they just look so happy I guess.

02:09:49.800 --> 02:09:51.380
And I, I said there's a feeling

02:09:51.380 --> 02:09:54.290
of people just feeling
optimistic and good,

02:09:54.290 --> 02:09:55.990
and this is one of
those pictures there

02:09:55.990 --> 02:09:58.350
that is like that.

02:09:58.350 --> 02:10:00.410
This was in the tent.

02:10:00.410 --> 02:10:03.490
And this is in the tent
of the first town meeting.

02:10:03.490 --> 02:10:06.720
I don't think it was
called the Soul Tent yet.

02:10:06.720 --> 02:10:12.330
That may have arrived after a
lot of music was performed there

02:10:12.330 --> 02:10:14.530
and people said that's
Soul Town.

02:10:14.530 --> 02:10:18.950
But this point it was just it.

02:10:18.950 --> 02:10:21.470
That guy in the poncho
you'll see a moment,

02:10:21.470 --> 02:10:22.820
there he's, he's on the right.

02:10:22.820 --> 02:10:24.250
His name is Sweet Willy.

02:10:24.250 --> 02:10:29.880
Sweet Willy had lost an arm in
Vietnam, and he's on the tape.

02:10:29.880 --> 02:10:31.840
He was an incredible speaker.

02:10:31.840 --> 02:10:35.950
You can see that guy with
him, just adoring people.

02:10:35.950 --> 02:10:38.490
And I, I was [inaudible]
Sweet Willy.

02:10:38.490 --> 02:10:40.970
I think the, the
only white guys I saw

02:10:40.970 --> 02:10:47.210
in the tent were the newsmen
and Alan Lomax and, and me,

02:10:47.210 --> 02:10:50.330
there may have been others,
but I didn't notice them.

02:10:50.330 --> 02:10:54.010
But I said other people started
coming and this is Kirk paying.

02:10:54.010 --> 02:10:56.630
Again he was so neat.

02:10:56.630 --> 02:11:00.090
And these are kids who were just
digging it, they just liked it.

02:11:00.090 --> 02:11:01.460
There were a lot of kids.

02:11:01.460 --> 02:11:04.890
And this is the, the gondola
of the news guy sitting there

02:11:04.890 --> 02:11:08.540
in the center of it during it.

02:11:08.540 --> 02:11:13.610
Over the telephone wire in there
you see a slightly oblong object

02:11:13.610 --> 02:11:14.910
over the guide.

02:11:14.910 --> 02:11:17.370
By the way, it was a
little mud there already,

02:11:17.370 --> 02:11:19.040
I don't remember it
raining but it looks

02:11:19.040 --> 02:11:22.970
like it was anticipating
what was going to happen.

02:11:22.970 --> 02:11:25.630
And there is the object,

02:11:25.630 --> 02:11:28.150
it's some kids playing
with a football.

02:11:28.150 --> 02:11:32.740
And that's Alan Lomax and
Kirk carrying the song sheets

02:11:32.740 --> 02:11:35.720
which had been prepared
by people

02:11:35.720 --> 02:11:39.930
at a publication
called Broadside.

02:11:39.930 --> 02:11:42.220
They put together
a number of songs.

02:11:42.220 --> 02:11:46.070
And the library has some now,
I've written them down with me.

02:11:46.070 --> 02:11:48.440
And they contain some
traditional songs

02:11:48.440 --> 02:11:50.570
and adaptations to
some traditional songs

02:11:50.570 --> 02:11:53.040
and a number of songs by Kirk.

02:11:53.040 --> 02:11:56.440
And that's Kirk again.

02:11:56.440 --> 02:12:00.190
And he would -- he would
do this all day long.

02:12:00.190 --> 02:12:02.520
That's Bessie Jones and
Georgia C. Highland.

02:12:02.520 --> 02:12:05.680
And that's at Ralph
Winkler's house.

02:12:05.680 --> 02:12:07.900
We heard Libya Cotton
before singing,

02:12:07.900 --> 02:12:10.040
oh Libya worked for Ralph.

02:12:10.040 --> 02:12:13.120
Libya played guitar left
handed, used to drive me crazy.

02:12:13.120 --> 02:12:14.920
I had [inaudible].

02:12:14.920 --> 02:12:20.090
[ Laughter ]

02:12:20.090 --> 02:12:23.420
He was one of the, Georgia
C. Highland singers,

02:12:23.420 --> 02:12:25.070
and what he sang to me there,

02:12:25.070 --> 02:12:32.120
that afternoon they had taken
him over to the rotunda.

02:12:32.120 --> 02:12:33.720
They'd been -- they'd
been on the capital

02:12:33.720 --> 02:12:36.140
and he'd been in the rotunda.

02:12:36.140 --> 02:12:41.610
And he said, I know why these
people are so screwed up,

02:12:41.610 --> 02:12:44.280
they got their big round room.

02:12:44.280 --> 02:12:47.380
You can't get your head
right in a big round room.

02:12:47.380 --> 02:12:49.510
You need to know
where the corners are.

02:12:49.510 --> 02:12:56.100
[ Laughter ]

02:12:56.100 --> 02:12:57.970
And this was in the tent.

02:12:57.970 --> 02:12:59.270
And this is the kind of thing

02:12:59.270 --> 02:13:01.230
that you just saw
there all the time.

02:13:01.230 --> 02:13:04.090
People just playing in the pool.

02:13:04.090 --> 02:13:05.420
People being by a pool.

02:13:05.420 --> 02:13:10.020
This was some tourist kid, and
this was a kid out of the camp.

02:13:10.020 --> 02:13:12.880
And they were wondering --
By the why where camp was,

02:13:12.880 --> 02:13:14.300
where Resurrection City was

02:13:14.300 --> 02:13:16.900
if you didn't know the
site, reflecting pool.

02:13:16.900 --> 02:13:19.540
And this is a stand of trees.

02:13:19.540 --> 02:13:21.310
And Resurrection City
is the other side

02:13:21.310 --> 02:13:22.880
of the stand of trees.

02:13:22.880 --> 02:13:24.200
You could walk around the pool

02:13:24.200 --> 02:13:26.020
and not see it if
you didn't look.

02:13:26.020 --> 02:13:28.850
If you didn't want to know it
was there you could pretend it

02:13:28.850 --> 02:13:30.150
wasn't there.

02:13:30.150 --> 02:13:31.450
So there would be
tourists around there,

02:13:31.450 --> 02:13:33.330
they just drove around,
having no idea

02:13:33.330 --> 02:13:37.580
that there was 3,000 people
you know 15 yards away.

02:13:37.580 --> 02:13:43.830
This is the beginning --
this is Solidarity Day.

02:13:43.830 --> 02:13:46.950
And I was always really happy
they called it Solidarity Day

02:13:46.950 --> 02:13:50.710
rather than [inaudible] Day
because that's what it was.

02:13:50.710 --> 02:13:53.840
Resurrection City, as you
heard before, was a --

02:13:53.840 --> 02:13:59.800
it involved black people, it
involved Native Americans,

02:13:59.800 --> 02:14:03.820
it involved Hispanics,
it involved white people.

02:14:03.820 --> 02:14:05.770
And what brought people
together was poverty.

02:14:05.770 --> 02:14:10.690
And I think it's the first major
event of that kind that brought

02:14:10.690 --> 02:14:14.710
so many people together
and made them aware

02:14:14.710 --> 02:14:17.030
that they shared
things in common

02:14:17.030 --> 02:14:21.080
that might be working
along in common.

02:14:21.080 --> 02:14:24.650
Solidarity Day went
one step further,

02:14:24.650 --> 02:14:27.210
because the union showed up.

02:14:27.210 --> 02:14:30.270
And the unions had been
notably absent from much

02:14:30.270 --> 02:14:32.430
of the civil rights stuff.

02:14:32.430 --> 02:14:35.410
And I mentioned several of
them before, there's one more

02:14:35.410 --> 02:14:42.810
that I forgot to mention, and
that was October 22, 1963.

02:14:42.810 --> 02:14:46.650
And October 22, 1963 was the day

02:14:46.650 --> 02:14:52.700
of the first six digit antiwar
demonstration in Washington.

02:14:52.700 --> 02:14:55.510
There had been antiwar
movements, I think it's going

02:14:55.510 --> 02:14:58.050
on for the last year and a half.

02:14:58.050 --> 02:15:00.040
But that was a big one.

02:15:00.040 --> 02:15:03.740
And one of the things that was
in the air, part of the spirit

02:15:03.740 --> 02:15:07.140
of all of us I think,
was that what was going

02:15:07.140 --> 02:15:09.790
on with the antiwar
movement, what was going

02:15:09.790 --> 02:15:12.190
on with the voting rights
movement, what was going

02:15:12.190 --> 02:15:15.140
on with poverty movement,
we had things

02:15:15.140 --> 02:15:17.530
in common with each other.

02:15:17.530 --> 02:15:21.750
And it wasn't all, you
know, use your, you here,

02:15:21.750 --> 02:15:23.100
you here and you there.

02:15:23.100 --> 02:15:25.250
That, the -- some
of the things wrong

02:15:25.250 --> 02:15:29.890
in the world we didn't have
to change too many nouns.

02:15:29.890 --> 02:15:32.020
It just kind of filled
the energy.

02:15:32.020 --> 02:15:34.450
And so this crowd reminded me

02:15:34.450 --> 02:15:36.880
of that crowd only
seven months earlier,

02:15:36.880 --> 02:15:39.290
in exactly the same place.

02:15:39.290 --> 02:15:42.410
And this crowd, as you'll
notice, everybody's there.

02:15:42.410 --> 02:15:44.980
All kinds of people.

02:15:44.980 --> 02:15:53.040
And at this one I was not
a participant, I was a --

02:15:53.040 --> 02:15:56.790
demonstrations like this unless,
unless you happened to luck

02:15:56.790 --> 02:15:59.460
out with I'd been to
the mountain and one

02:15:59.460 --> 02:16:01.430
of those which is very rare.

02:16:01.430 --> 02:16:02.880
You don't listen
to the speeches,

02:16:02.880 --> 02:16:04.700
you can't hear them
most of the time.

02:16:04.700 --> 02:16:08.170
What you're doing is you're
bearing witness with your body

02:16:08.170 --> 02:16:11.970
to say this matters I want to
be here with these other people,

02:16:11.970 --> 02:16:14.940
count us you son of a
bitch, we're watching you.

02:16:14.940 --> 02:16:18.530
And that's what was
going on there.

02:16:24.050 --> 02:16:25.370
There's that Klansman again.

02:16:25.370 --> 02:16:28.300
That, now that's Abernathy's at
the microphone and [inaudible]

02:16:28.300 --> 02:16:29.600
and Coretta Scott King.

02:16:29.600 --> 02:16:32.880
I only realized when I
was making these prints,

02:16:32.880 --> 02:16:34.770
she there she is,
I only realized --

02:16:34.770 --> 02:16:37.940
I never realized
before she was in there.

02:16:37.940 --> 02:16:39.240
I knew she must have
been there and I,

02:16:39.240 --> 02:16:41.040
and I had never looked
until last week, I --

02:16:41.040 --> 02:16:47.410
[ Inaudible ]

02:16:47.410 --> 02:16:48.710
Yeah right.

02:16:48.710 --> 02:16:53.510
Oh I'm sure if I blew up that
across the, there would be a lot

02:16:53.510 --> 02:16:54.810
of people you could name it.

02:16:54.810 --> 02:16:56.440
And there's the press again.

02:16:56.440 --> 02:17:02.030
Some guys got into trouble
after this happened.

02:17:02.030 --> 02:17:05.350
Oh and this picture
I really liked.

02:17:05.350 --> 02:17:10.770
This could have been a 1930's
WPA picture with those hats.

02:17:10.770 --> 02:17:13.500
And again, people
of all ages at it.

02:17:13.500 --> 02:17:19.420
And labor people, people from
just all kinds of things.

02:17:19.420 --> 02:17:24.020
This guy, a lot of white
guys with crossed arms.

02:17:24.020 --> 02:17:27.040
And, and she, she looks so cool.

02:17:27.040 --> 02:17:28.510
I love her body language.

02:17:28.510 --> 02:17:30.360
And, and his.

02:17:30.360 --> 02:17:33.830
And you see -- you see those
guys down by the street, those,

02:17:33.830 --> 02:17:36.710
those two guys in the left
with their crossed arms?

02:17:36.710 --> 02:17:38.450
They work for somebody.

02:17:38.450 --> 02:17:43.510
You know you, they, they weren't
there enjoying the venue.

02:17:43.510 --> 02:17:48.040
[ Laughter ]

02:17:48.040 --> 02:17:52.340
And, and again, while this is
going on, the kids being kids.

02:17:52.340 --> 02:17:55.170
So those are the
pictures I took.

02:17:55.170 --> 02:17:57.510
Okay. Thank you.

