notes here, of an institution

02:20:54.950 --> 02:20:59.340
within the institution at Yale,
called the Black Workshop.

02:20:59.340 --> 02:21:04.320
Yale had, had the
foresight to understand

02:21:04.320 --> 02:21:10.540
that cities were being
reconfigured, and I'm talking

02:21:10.540 --> 02:21:13.670
like the, the mid '60s.

02:21:13.670 --> 02:21:15.370
And the School of Architecture,

02:21:15.370 --> 02:21:18.670
Charles Moore was the
head of that school.

02:21:18.670 --> 02:21:21.500
And they were sort of building
monuments to themselves,

02:21:21.500 --> 02:21:26.900
in terms of some of the
architectural designs

02:21:26.900 --> 02:21:30.150
that were being executed
during those days.

02:21:30.150 --> 02:21:35.170
And so a group of us
sort of connected,

02:21:35.170 --> 02:21:38.050
formed what we called the
Black Workshop, and were able

02:21:38.050 --> 02:21:42.680
to get the university to
find us a space outside

02:21:42.680 --> 02:21:47.300
of the school house, and we
were able to bring in people

02:21:47.300 --> 02:21:49.130
who we thought were experts.

02:21:49.130 --> 02:21:53.250
And we spent a lot of
time in the street.

02:21:53.250 --> 02:21:56.560
We were in Newark, New
Jersey, helping to develop one

02:21:56.560 --> 02:21:59.560
of the first daycare complexes.

02:21:59.560 --> 02:22:02.250
We were in Boston and Chinatown.

02:22:02.250 --> 02:22:05.960
We're predominately city
planners and architects.

02:22:05.960 --> 02:22:08.830
And I was the, sort of
the lone visual guy.

02:22:08.830 --> 02:22:11.570
I was learning graphic
design, but I was headed

02:22:11.570 --> 02:22:13.910
into photography and film.

02:22:13.910 --> 02:22:18.340
And so I became the one who
documented what every --

02:22:18.340 --> 02:22:20.280
everything that was going on.

02:22:20.280 --> 02:22:26.390
And so these images
really were the --

02:22:26.390 --> 02:22:29.140
that was really the foundation
for, for the work that I,

02:22:29.140 --> 02:22:31.440
that I moved on to do.

02:22:40.660 --> 02:22:43.250
This one, okay.

02:22:43.250 --> 02:22:48.770
I got to, to, to
here, Washington DC

02:22:48.770 --> 02:22:53.050
because as I had said
earlier, I, I, I'd really felt

02:22:53.050 --> 02:22:58.500
that I needed to
be actively doing.

02:22:58.500 --> 02:23:04.450
And I left the class, got
on a plane, came down here,

02:23:04.450 --> 02:23:08.550
checked into the Holiday
Inn and, and spent a couple

02:23:08.550 --> 02:23:15.340
of days making images and, and
that was really my first attempt

02:23:15.340 --> 02:23:22.920
to use the camera to, to -- in a
serious way cover a march and a,

02:23:22.920 --> 02:23:27.150
and a situation like this.

02:23:27.150 --> 02:23:32.320
So I, nevertheless I made my way
through the city engaging folks,

02:23:32.320 --> 02:23:35.830
making portrait's, looking
for images supporting,

02:23:35.830 --> 02:23:39.570
supporting activities going
on including a baptism,

02:23:39.570 --> 02:23:42.240
food preparation, a barbershop.

02:23:42.240 --> 02:23:45.730
I really, I recall generally
trying to capture images

02:23:45.730 --> 02:23:49.100
that would attempt to tell a
story of life in the village

02:23:49.100 --> 02:23:51.670
as well as during the march.

02:23:59.040 --> 02:24:02.520
The theme of the march and
encampment, as we all know,

02:24:02.520 --> 02:24:05.670
came from Dr. King's vision
to create a broad coalition

02:24:05.670 --> 02:24:09.120
of workers to highlight the
gross inequities our system

02:24:09.120 --> 02:24:11.020
of democracy fosters.

02:24:11.020 --> 02:24:15.390
His assassination just months
before had, had made --

02:24:15.390 --> 02:24:17.630
had been tied directly
to his emphasis

02:24:17.630 --> 02:24:20.620
on the economic injustice
I felt.

02:24:20.620 --> 02:24:22.330
Today the question can be asked,

02:24:22.330 --> 02:24:26.740
has the situation gotten any
better, or is it worse in terms

02:24:26.740 --> 02:24:30.110
of economic divide that exists

02:24:30.110 --> 02:24:33.260
between the haves
and the have nots.

02:24:33.260 --> 02:24:39.930
And this, this graphic
speaks to a recent survey

02:24:39.930 --> 02:24:43.870
that was done in, in
Boston by the Boston Globe.

02:24:43.870 --> 02:24:48.980
And really is, is,
is startling to --

02:24:48.980 --> 02:24:54.010
when we understand that
in a city like Boston,

02:24:54.010 --> 02:25:01.070
that the net worth of, of a,
of a black family is, is $8.

02:25:01.070 --> 02:25:07.130
And that we really
have to push, push on.

02:25:07.130 --> 02:25:12.630
We really have to, to address
and, and many of the ways

02:25:12.630 --> 02:25:18.870
that were discussed
earlier this vast dichotomy.

02:25:18.870 --> 02:25:24.540
As I mentioned, I'm on the
right there, and I'm --

02:25:24.540 --> 02:25:27.330
this is our, part of our
black workshop in New Haven

02:25:27.330 --> 02:25:30.180
which was in it's infancy.

02:25:30.180 --> 02:25:32.890
And it was really, as I've
mentioned, my launching pad

02:25:32.890 --> 02:25:38.100
into coming down
here to do this work.

02:25:38.100 --> 02:25:41.060
And as a graduate student, I
was learning the discipline

02:25:41.060 --> 02:25:45.570
of graphic design but
was also shooting a film

02:25:45.570 --> 02:25:51.500
on my experiences, which I later
used to get my certificate,

02:25:51.500 --> 02:25:55.900
my degree to get out of Yale.

02:25:55.900 --> 02:26:00.490
And, and which served, you know,

02:26:00.490 --> 02:26:04.230
that Black Workshop continued
ten years after we left.

02:26:04.230 --> 02:26:07.700
So we were actually involved
in recruiting students.

02:26:07.700 --> 02:26:10.850
We were involved in
shaping the curriculum.

02:26:10.850 --> 02:26:17.470
Where up and down on a book
that we're writing at the moment

02:26:17.470 --> 02:26:23.890
from '68 to '70, which talks
about how we had some impact

02:26:23.890 --> 02:26:27.110
on an institution like
Yale and other institutions

02:26:27.110 --> 02:26:30.940
in the country, teach
architecture.

02:26:30.940 --> 02:26:37.190
The, the notion that you learn
a discipline and then you go

02:26:37.190 --> 02:26:43.540
to the client and give the
client what you think the client

02:26:43.540 --> 02:26:48.090
should have was the way
architecture had been taught

02:26:48.090 --> 02:26:49.440
for many, many years.

02:26:49.440 --> 02:26:55.580
And so our group began
to make major adjustments

02:26:55.580 --> 02:26:59.670
to that practice and, and
we're beginning to understand,

02:26:59.670 --> 02:27:03.400
you know, what our role was
during that time in New Haven.

02:27:03.400 --> 02:27:06.190
We, we, we thought
everything kind

02:27:06.190 --> 02:27:08.720
of centered in, in New Haven.

02:27:08.720 --> 02:27:11.970
We, we had -- we had the,
the Panther trial was going

02:27:11.970 --> 02:27:15.030
on with Bobby Seale,
the Alex Rackley case

02:27:15.030 --> 02:27:18.030
that sprung up out of that.

02:27:18.030 --> 02:27:22.380
The Panther office was maybe
two or three doors down from

02:27:22.380 --> 02:27:28.840
where we resided as
the Black Workshop.

02:27:28.840 --> 02:27:34.490
And this is an image of, of,
of one of the many gatherings

02:27:34.490 --> 02:27:39.780
in front of the office there.

02:27:39.780 --> 02:27:43.530
Getting back to Resurrection
City,

02:27:43.530 --> 02:27:50.320
we can see here the attempt
to, to mark space as well

02:27:50.320 --> 02:27:59.390
as to indicate the, the nature
of the climatic conditions

02:27:59.390 --> 02:28:06.050
which means that the sneakers
being hung for dry on the line.

02:28:06.050 --> 02:28:16.060
And but this is just a, a view
of as far as one could see.

02:28:16.060 --> 02:28:19.040
And, and I'm going to look at
that to the end of that image.

