A different,

02:28:21.640 --> 02:28:22.940
a different way from now.

02:28:22.940 --> 02:28:24.240
I'm talking about --

02:28:24.240 --> 02:28:25.540
&gt;&gt; Unidentified Speaker:
Oh into the [inaudible].

02:28:25.540 --> 02:28:26.840
&gt;&gt; Reginald Jackson:
I'm talking about the,

02:28:26.840 --> 02:28:28.200
the yeah the monument.

02:28:28.200 --> 02:28:33.950
And you know once again
signage means a lot.

02:28:33.950 --> 02:28:37.930
And, and that spoke to
the, the need for security,

02:28:37.930 --> 02:28:43.260
which I hadn't really thought
about or anticipated and,

02:28:46.130 --> 02:28:50.820
and the repetition of the
feed, of ending hunger.

02:28:50.820 --> 02:29:00.600
This image speaks to the
ability of families to,

02:29:00.600 --> 02:29:06.580
to hang in there, to, to
persevere during that time.

02:29:06.580 --> 02:29:10.180
And the press oddly enough
didn't really say a whole lot,

02:29:10.180 --> 02:29:13.890
I thought, about white
involvement in the,

02:29:13.890 --> 02:29:16.260
in the, in the encampment.

02:29:16.260 --> 02:29:22.120
And so I think, you know,
more and more efforts need

02:29:22.120 --> 02:29:25.960
to show the diversity
that existed there.

02:29:31.040 --> 02:29:33.340
And --

02:29:37.040 --> 02:29:40.400
So we begin to see, you
know a much broader view of,

02:29:40.400 --> 02:29:43.810
of what was going on.

02:29:45.400 --> 02:29:48.750
And finally,

02:29:48.750 --> 02:29:53.900
the intergenerational
nature of folk.

02:29:53.900 --> 02:30:01.780
And a view from, from
within I call this.

02:30:06.050 --> 02:30:08.350
And as far as the eye could see.

02:30:13.050 --> 02:30:19.510
And this image takes us beyond
the march and immediately

02:30:19.510 --> 02:30:22.940
after graduation in 1970,

02:30:22.940 --> 02:30:28.060
I and some colleagues raised a
little bit of money and went off

02:30:28.060 --> 02:30:32.670
to West Africa, Ghana and
Liberia in particular.

02:30:32.670 --> 02:30:43.830
And when I saw the conditions,
particularly in, in Liberia

02:30:43.830 --> 02:30:48.140
and Ghana, I began to
think about my experiences

02:30:48.140 --> 02:30:49.690
that I had just encountered here

02:30:49.690 --> 02:30:51.910
and my experiences
here in the US.

02:30:51.910 --> 02:30:57.810
And I found this, this woman
who, and you know I'm speaking

02:30:57.810 --> 02:31:01.110
about how that impacted
what I later,

02:31:01.110 --> 02:31:03.570
what my vision became later.

02:31:03.570 --> 02:31:09.910
Talks about the, the exploited
nature of the multinationals

02:31:09.910 --> 02:31:18.650
and how corporations and
how they had been able

02:31:18.650 --> 02:31:21.700
to without too much
interruption continue

02:31:21.700 --> 02:31:27.100
to exploit the raw materials
that exists and are extracted

02:31:27.100 --> 02:31:29.550
out of those countries
in West Africa.

02:31:29.550 --> 02:31:38.000
And so this woman's stance to me
speaks of, you know, that, that,

02:31:38.000 --> 02:31:41.810
the courage that's necessary
to try to break that,

02:31:41.810 --> 02:31:44.220
that stronghold,

02:31:44.220 --> 02:31:50.230
the strangulation of,
of these countries.

02:31:50.230 --> 02:31:51.920
Saying enough is enough.

02:31:51.920 --> 02:31:55.060
Like your grandmother
or your mom or you aunt,

02:31:55.060 --> 02:31:57.810
when they put the
hands on their hips,

02:31:57.810 --> 02:32:00.110
you know, enough is enough.

02:32:05.060 --> 02:32:09.870
This is a, you know, as a, as
a visual artist one of the hats

02:32:09.870 --> 02:32:16.860
that I wear, the -- as a
photo collage which I made

02:32:16.860 --> 02:32:22.870
into a poster which reflects
my feelings after leaving Ghana

02:32:22.870 --> 02:32:26.450
and I think I did this in 1972.

02:32:26.450 --> 02:32:28.590
And it, it shows
the trains moving

02:32:28.590 --> 02:32:31.850
out of the country,
going one way.

02:32:31.850 --> 02:32:36.400
It, it shows a man in the bush
with a chicken in one hand,

02:32:36.400 --> 02:32:39.300
and an attaché case
in the other.

02:32:39.300 --> 02:32:45.630
It shows another man with a
child emblazoned on his heart.

02:32:45.630 --> 02:32:51.410
And then you see this young
person, piercing eyes,

02:32:51.410 --> 02:32:58.180
through this tire representing
the, the rubber plantations,

02:32:58.180 --> 02:33:03.790
and various other plantations
that existed and still exist in,

02:33:03.790 --> 02:33:05.680
in parts of West Africa.

02:33:05.680 --> 02:33:11.380
I call it the last frontier.

02:33:11.380 --> 02:33:15.900
This image is part
of a network of ports

02:33:15.900 --> 02:33:18.420
and castles along
the Ghana coast

02:33:18.420 --> 02:33:22.800
that were used during the
Transatlantic slave trade.

02:33:22.800 --> 02:33:29.330
This is Fort Amsterdam built
in the 1600's by the Dutch.

02:33:29.330 --> 02:33:33.360
And consequently over the
years it's been switched back

02:33:33.360 --> 02:33:37.390
and forth, one country would,
would come and capture the fort

02:33:37.390 --> 02:33:40.980
and they'd name it something
else and then they would be,

02:33:40.980 --> 02:33:42.680
it would, would go
back and forth.

02:33:42.680 --> 02:33:51.380
And so this image I feel is
important to, to show that many

02:33:51.380 --> 02:33:54.210
of the, the ancestors of
African Americans passed

02:33:54.210 --> 02:33:57.750
through these forts
along the Ghana coast.

02:33:57.750 --> 02:34:05.720
And the, that is an important
connector to this image.

02:34:05.720 --> 02:34:09.810
This is an image of the
African meeting house in Boston.

02:34:09.810 --> 02:34:15.960
It's a photo serigraph that
I was commissioned to do

02:34:15.960 --> 02:34:18.220
for the Bicentennial in Boston.

02:34:18.220 --> 02:34:25.930
And it's, it employs the sort
of iconographic ivory pendant

02:34:25.930 --> 02:34:28.310
that was sacked from
the City of Bennie

02:34:28.310 --> 02:34:30.140
at the turn of the last century.

02:34:30.140 --> 02:34:35.890
And I'm superimposed this image
over the African Meeting House,

02:34:35.890 --> 02:34:40.300
which is the oldest church
built by all black labor

02:34:40.300 --> 02:34:44.480
in the United States,
still standing, 1806.

02:34:44.480 --> 02:34:49.280
And another part
of my journey is,

02:34:49.280 --> 02:34:51.650
has been dealing
with the homeless.

02:34:51.650 --> 02:34:57.670
And this is an image that shows
a connection to institutions

02:34:57.670 --> 02:35:02.040
that were, were formed
to, to help the needy.

02:35:02.040 --> 02:35:08.700
I began to do work in the
community on homelessness

02:35:08.700 --> 02:35:12.780
and produced this book along
with a Mass Association

02:35:12.780 --> 02:35:16.530
for Mental Health as an
integrated approach to,

02:35:16.530 --> 02:35:19.720
to dealing with services
surrounding the homeless.

02:35:19.720 --> 02:35:23.020
This would have been
the early '80s.

02:35:23.020 --> 02:35:26.410
This is one of the images that
I made on the street of a woman,

02:35:26.410 --> 02:35:30.840
Inez, who was homeless
and who, who lived once --

02:35:30.840 --> 02:35:33.810
who actually had
property on Beacon Hill

02:35:33.810 --> 02:35:36.460
at one point, who is homeless.

02:35:36.460 --> 02:35:42.400
And this is a current photograph
of the Poor People's Campaign

02:35:42.400 --> 02:35:47.690
in Boston at the state house
on Monday, this, this week.

02:35:47.690 --> 02:35:51.620
Another view.

02:35:51.620 --> 02:35:55.110
And finally, this is a
poster that I created

02:35:55.110 --> 02:35:58.120
for an antiracism organization
that I've been working

02:35:58.120 --> 02:36:04.590
for as I left Simmons
back in the '90s.

02:36:04.590 --> 02:36:07.560
And it, it says, I don't know
if you can make it out, it says,

02:36:07.560 --> 02:36:10.910
we don't want our chains
made more bearable,

02:36:10.910 --> 02:36:13.130
we want them removed.

02:36:13.130 --> 02:36:19.680
And that has been an image that
has been used throughout the,

02:36:19.680 --> 02:36:24.460
the course of this
community change organization.

02:36:24.460 --> 02:36:31.100
So this is an example of how I,
how I have traversed this course

02:36:31.100 --> 02:36:34.780
since my days in the '60s.

