02:37:32.980 --> 02:37:36.890
So I have approached
the commemoration

02:37:36.890 --> 02:37:39.810
of the 50th Anniversary
of 1960 as well

02:37:39.810 --> 02:37:42.900
as the historian and,
and as a curator.

02:37:42.900 --> 02:37:48.060
Back in 2016, I decided that DC,
which is where I'm from needed

02:37:48.060 --> 02:37:52.620
to have a yearlong commemoration
of the entire year of 1968.

02:37:52.620 --> 02:37:54.080
And you get to have
a commemoration

02:37:54.080 --> 02:37:57.510
that would highlight
activism, art, architecture,

02:37:57.510 --> 02:38:00.650
and everyday life,
all of which made 1968

02:38:00.650 --> 02:38:02.530
such an incredible
year here in DC.

02:38:02.530 --> 02:38:04.860
And of course these
are all elements

02:38:04.860 --> 02:38:07.390
of the Poor People's Campaign
and the Resurrection City,

02:38:07.390 --> 02:38:09.800
as panelists have been sharing.

02:38:09.800 --> 02:38:11.990
The Commemoration had
to be public facing,

02:38:11.990 --> 02:38:15.150
had to be committed to
providing the public with a full

02:38:15.150 --> 02:38:18.060
and complex exploration
of the city in 1968.

02:38:18.060 --> 02:38:21.410
And it had to be a commemoration
in which Washingtonians

02:38:21.410 --> 02:38:24.830
who were here in 1968,
were actually recognized.

02:38:24.830 --> 02:38:26.880
And finally, it had
to be a commemoration

02:38:26.880 --> 02:38:30.010
that would show others
that DC, as a capital city,

02:38:30.010 --> 02:38:33.370
and as an international capital,
like Kingston, like Mexico,

02:38:33.370 --> 02:38:38.950
like Paris, like Prague also
had much to teach the world.

02:38:38.950 --> 02:38:40.910
And so I approached
this commemorative goal

02:38:40.910 --> 02:38:42.490
as three different ways.

02:38:42.490 --> 02:38:45.570
The first was by convening
a group of culture producers

02:38:45.570 --> 02:38:48.720
from monthly meetings so that
we could meet each other,

02:38:48.720 --> 02:38:51.610
learn about events that
were being planned and also

02:38:51.610 --> 02:38:53.480
to collaborate on events.

02:38:53.480 --> 02:38:55.550
And some of those
culture producers are here

02:38:55.550 --> 02:38:56.850
in the audience.

02:38:56.850 --> 02:39:01.510
And I'm happy, really, really
happy to say that we began 2018

02:39:01.510 --> 02:39:05.700
with a daylong kick off even at
the National Building Museum,

02:39:05.700 --> 02:39:08.710
was a daylong event
where we had symposium.

02:39:08.710 --> 02:39:12.500
There was artists, there
were people sharing objects.

02:39:12.500 --> 02:39:15.870
And there was also the national
symphony orchestra quartet

02:39:15.870 --> 02:39:20.490
actually did an hour long
concert sharing songs

02:39:20.490 --> 02:39:22.210
about human rights.

02:39:22.210 --> 02:39:24.480
It was an amazing,
an amazing event.

02:39:24.480 --> 02:39:26.640
And also really powerful
because as, as I'll talk

02:39:26.640 --> 02:39:29.520
about a little later, that
generally when you think

02:39:29.520 --> 02:39:32.710
about DC in 1968, people
aren't thinking about January

02:39:32.710 --> 02:39:34.370
through December,
particularly the media.

02:39:34.370 --> 02:39:35.860
They're thinking about DC

02:39:35.860 --> 02:39:39.020
in '68 is really April
4th through April 8th.

02:39:39.020 --> 02:39:41.050
So the fact that cultural
producers were able

02:39:41.050 --> 02:39:44.000
to get together and actually
start an event in January,

02:39:44.000 --> 02:39:46.180
I think was really important.

02:39:46.180 --> 02:39:49.370
The second thing
that I've done is to,

02:39:49.370 --> 02:39:53.040
to bring about this
commemorative goal was also

02:39:53.040 --> 02:39:57.410
doing extensive research in
archives and libraries here

02:39:57.410 --> 02:40:00.490
in this city, doing extensive
research here at the Library

02:40:00.490 --> 02:40:03.240
of Congress, at the
DC Public Library,

02:40:03.240 --> 02:40:05.610
Howard University
[inaudible] Research Center,

02:40:05.610 --> 02:40:09.040
George Washington University
and a whole host of places.

02:40:09.040 --> 02:40:12.050
And one of the things that
I've also learned as well is

02:40:12.050 --> 02:40:14.580
that there are a range of
Washingtonians individuals

02:40:14.580 --> 02:40:18.740
but also organizations that
also have archives, largely,

02:40:18.740 --> 02:40:20.040
that have not been tapped.

02:40:20.040 --> 02:40:21.340
And so that's one of the things

02:40:21.340 --> 02:40:22.730
that I've been invested
in doing.

02:40:22.730 --> 02:40:25.150
And so I've been reaching
out to native Washingtonians

02:40:25.150 --> 02:40:28.630
for their stories and for their
photographs, because I wanted

02:40:28.630 --> 02:40:31.380
to show how engaged
Washingtonians were

02:40:31.380 --> 02:40:33.690
with their city and
the world around them.

02:40:33.690 --> 02:40:35.680
And of course has been
stated before that none

02:40:35.680 --> 02:40:36.980
of the national events,

02:40:36.980 --> 02:40:39.710
including the Poor People's
Campaign, and Resurrection City,

02:40:39.710 --> 02:40:43.600
could have been executed without
the help of Washingtonians.

02:40:43.600 --> 02:40:48.000
And the third way of course is
by curating the DC 1968 project

02:40:48.000 --> 02:40:50.900
which Guha alerted,
alluded to earlier.

02:40:50.900 --> 02:40:52.700
And which I developed in part

02:40:52.700 --> 02:40:55.650
to create a visually
compelling counter narrative

02:40:55.650 --> 02:40:59.340
to the hybrid focus on the
uprising after the assassination

02:40:59.340 --> 02:41:01.280
of Reverend, of Reverend
Dr. Martin Luther King,

02:41:01.280 --> 02:41:03.890
Jr. And I'm not going
to do that today,

02:41:03.890 --> 02:41:07.150
and I know you have your phones
off, but if you haven't already,

02:41:07.150 --> 02:41:11.270
all you can do is do a browser
search for Washington DC 1968

02:41:11.270 --> 02:41:16.000
and see what comes up, see
the images that come up.

02:41:16.000 --> 02:41:18.360
Here's the slides.

02:41:18.360 --> 02:41:21.670
In honor of Father's Day,
this is an image of my father,

02:41:21.670 --> 02:41:26.640
Bobby Hale, who was a native
Washingtonian, a Korean War vet,

02:41:26.640 --> 02:41:28.910
and also a lifelong
photographer.

02:41:28.910 --> 02:41:32.820
And I believe this is a selfie
that he took of himself in 1970

02:41:32.820 --> 02:41:34.950
with his beloved Nikon camera.

02:41:34.950 --> 02:41:40.330
So after I told him about
my desire to curate 1968

02:41:40.330 --> 02:41:43.330
for this city, he's very
nonchalant, he's like,

02:41:43.330 --> 02:41:44.630
yeah that's interesting.

02:41:44.630 --> 02:41:47.810
And two weeks later, he brings
me a plain white envelope.

02:41:47.810 --> 02:41:51.190
And inside are more than
a dozen color photographs

02:41:51.190 --> 02:41:55.940
that he had taken of DC in
1968, DC in April and May.

02:41:55.940 --> 02:41:57.640
And the thing that's
interesting is

02:41:57.640 --> 02:41:59.700
that they were all color images.

02:41:59.700 --> 02:42:02.430
And I think that's important.

02:42:02.430 --> 02:42:05.330
His photographs offer an
important visual counter

02:42:05.330 --> 02:42:09.410
narrative to a, what I'm calling
a problematic visual trop.

02:42:09.410 --> 02:42:11.560
I know this academia, but
you have to bear with me.

02:42:11.560 --> 02:42:14.880
A problematic visual
trop often promulgated

02:42:14.880 --> 02:42:17.240
by local media outlets
like the Washington Post,

02:42:17.240 --> 02:42:18.860
a Washingtonian magazine.

02:42:18.860 --> 02:42:23.920
For them, too often DC in 1968
exists in black and white.

02:42:23.920 --> 02:42:26.460
The black and white have
destroyed buildings, smoke,

02:42:26.460 --> 02:42:29.520
the national guard, which
enveloped the city immediately

02:42:29.520 --> 02:42:32.110
after the assassination of
Reverend Dr. Martin Luther King,

02:42:32.110 --> 02:42:35.090
Jr. And obviously black
and white images existed,

02:42:35.090 --> 02:42:38.300
the uprising did exist, but
again what I'm arguing is

02:42:38.300 --> 02:42:41.190
that what they show in a
sense is that that's all

02:42:41.190 --> 02:42:43.320
that existed in DC in 1968.

02:42:43.320 --> 02:42:46.730
That's the only story that
we need to know about 1968.

02:42:46.730 --> 02:42:49.720
And as we've been hearing
there's so, so much more.

02:42:49.720 --> 02:42:52.880
Okay. And so what
they do usually,

02:42:52.880 --> 02:42:55.590
and I haven't actually
put the images up again

02:42:55.590 --> 02:42:58.130
because I think they're, this --

02:42:58.130 --> 02:43:00.360
that's all that you see that
I don't want to participate

02:43:00.360 --> 02:43:03.940
in that perpetuation
of this visual trop,

02:43:03.940 --> 02:43:05.730
so you get this little
fancy design that I've done.

02:43:05.730 --> 02:43:08.780
Maybe Reginald you'll
appreciate this design.

02:43:08.780 --> 02:43:11.700
But anyways, so generally,
general,

02:43:11.700 --> 02:43:13.260
you too Bruce, I apologize.

02:43:13.260 --> 02:43:16.260
So generally what you get is,
is a black and white image,

02:43:16.260 --> 02:43:19.030
again of, of sadness and
bad, and things that are bad.

02:43:19.030 --> 02:43:22.370
And it's contrasted on the
other side with, you know,

02:43:22.370 --> 02:43:26.790
a 2018 color image, usually,
you know a, a property,

02:43:26.790 --> 02:43:31.010
something that's beautiful, you
know something that represents,

02:43:31.010 --> 02:43:32.310
you know, this kind of moment

02:43:32.310 --> 02:43:34.020
of hyper development
and capitalism.

02:43:34.020 --> 02:43:38.330
So again 1968 bad,
2018 color good.

02:43:38.330 --> 02:43:41.050
But you know as I'm suggesting

02:43:41.050 --> 02:43:43.950
that this narrative
is very narrow,

02:43:43.950 --> 02:43:48.030
it's a historical
and problematic.

02:43:48.030 --> 02:43:50.940
We only have to look
at the visual narrative

02:43:50.940 --> 02:43:53.670
of the Poor People's
Campaign and Resurrection City

02:43:53.670 --> 02:43:57.310
to educate the public about
the danger of that visual trop.

02:43:57.310 --> 02:44:00.200
And this danger of this single
story, I'm actually borrowing

02:44:00.200 --> 02:44:03.120
from Chimamanda and Ngozi
Adichie's work who talks

02:44:03.120 --> 02:44:05.490
about the danger of
the single story.

02:44:05.490 --> 02:44:11.500
And so here is a recent
story from my DC 1968 project

02:44:11.500 --> 02:44:14.800
that beautifully, I think,
links the past and the present.

02:44:14.800 --> 02:44:19.560
This is a 2018 photograph
of a 1968 door insert

02:44:19.560 --> 02:44:22.750
from the Southern Christian
Leadership Campaign,

02:44:22.750 --> 02:44:25.840
Conferences, Poor People's
Campaign Headquarters that was

02:44:25.840 --> 02:44:28.260
at the corner of 14th
and U Streets, Northwest.

02:44:28.260 --> 02:44:30.040
Does anybody who remembers '68,

02:44:30.040 --> 02:44:31.680
does anybody remember
that door insert?

02:44:31.680 --> 02:44:33.540
Okay beautiful.

02:44:33.540 --> 02:44:36.660
So Carmen Gilmore and
Carole Green who were

02:44:36.660 --> 02:44:40.900
in their early 20's in 1968,
on their very first day

02:44:40.900 --> 02:44:44.450
of volunteering at the Poor
People's Campaign Headquarters,

02:44:44.450 --> 02:44:46.090
they met each other.

02:44:46.090 --> 02:44:50.410
They -- Carmen Gilmore was
a switchboard operator,

02:44:50.410 --> 02:44:52.660
and Carole Green was a drive.

02:44:52.660 --> 02:44:55.560
Does anyone remember
Carole Green as a driver?

02:44:55.560 --> 02:44:57.550
You think you remember it okay.

02:44:57.550 --> 02:45:00.980
So on that day, they
became friend, fast friends

02:45:00.980 --> 02:45:05.420
and a friendship that's
lasted for more than 50 years.

02:45:05.420 --> 02:45:08.040
And on that day was the
beginning of a commitment

02:45:08.040 --> 02:45:12.170
to activism that also lasted,
has lasted for 50 years.

02:45:12.170 --> 02:45:14.950
So after the Poor
People's Campaign ended,

02:45:14.950 --> 02:45:18.530
and the headquarters closed,
Green drove by the building

02:45:18.530 --> 02:45:22.050
in his red VW Beetle, and for
some reason he didn't just pass

02:45:22.050 --> 02:45:26.400
by going to his Adams Morgan
apartment and just stay home,

02:45:26.400 --> 02:45:29.950
he actually drove home,
went and grabbed his tools,

02:45:29.950 --> 02:45:32.500
and drove back to
the building to,

02:45:32.500 --> 02:45:35.450
what I'm calling
liberate the door.

02:45:35.450 --> 02:45:37.210
The door insert.

02:45:37.210 --> 02:45:39.780
For some reason decided not
to take the door, but he,

02:45:39.780 --> 02:45:44.340
he somehow was able to, to
take the insert out of the door

02:45:44.340 --> 02:45:47.340
and he drove it back
home in his Beetle.

02:45:47.340 --> 02:45:49.860
And he's kept it for 50 years.

02:45:49.860 --> 02:45:51.340
I mean it's, it's unbelievable.

02:45:51.340 --> 02:45:55.080
And actually just a few
months ago he donated it

02:45:55.080 --> 02:45:58.080
to the Smithsonian at the
Smithsonian Institution.

02:45:58.080 --> 02:46:01.000
So I think it's a
wonderful story.

